<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Banc Closed for Mismanagement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Uganda, central bank
of the east African country, Thursday declared that it has closed
the Greenland Bank Limited (GBL) for its mismanagement and huge
inside lending.
</P>
<P>
This decision was announced here by the central bank governor,
Charles Kikonyogo, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that from the day of closure, the commercial bank will
stop all its business affairs and operations with the public and
depositors.
</P>
<P>
The governor assured the depositors in the bank that the
central bank will protect their interests.
</P>
<P>
The financial conditions of the Greenland Bank have been
deteriorating over the past months and this closure is to stop the
bank from continuing to slide into the bottomless pit, he added.
</P>
<P>
As of the 41-billion-shilling (41 million U.S. dollars) loans
of the bank, 55 percent went to the companies connected with the
bank or its shareholders, the governor explained, adding that the
bank lost one billion shillings (one million dollars) due to
mismanagement over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
The Greenland Bank has hit headlines here not only because it
was warned from time to time due to its mismanagement, but because
it is the bank through which President Yoweri Museveni's brother
Salim Saleh, former senior presidential advisor on defense and
security, bought 49 percent shares in Uganda Commercial Bank
fraudulently.
</P>
<P>
Salim Saleh was forced to resign after this scandal surfaced
late last year and sparked public rage at the rampant corruption
and irregularities in the country's privatization process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
