<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament Adjourns As Requested by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Parliament has adjourned
prematurely following a formal request by the government to be
given more time to study the censure motions against Vice
President Specioza Kazibwe contained in the parliamentary select
committee report.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Speaker Francis Ayume Thursday
after Prime Minister Kintu Musoke had submitted the request, Radio
Uganda reported in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The request said that the government should study the
recommendations contained in the report thoroughly because they
concern the Vice President Kazibwe and her two junior ministers.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament has been in a hot debate on the fate of the vice
 president who is also the Minister of Agriculture, Animal
Industry and Fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The report, issued after investigations by the committee,
accuses Kazibwe and her two ministers of failing to supervise the
construction of the 15 valley dams which resulted in a loss of 3.4
billion shillings (3.4 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
A censure motion was drafted following the report and it was
backed by most MPs.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe protested her innocence, arguing that the plans for the
valley dam construction had been conceived much earlier before she
was given the ministerial seat.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe's case has been the biggest since the Parliament
embarked on exposing corruption among senior government officials.
So far two ministers have been censured.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament's unprecedented determination to weed corruption
resulted from both the ruling elite's willingness to promote
economic development and pressure from donor countries.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries, mostly European, demanded the Ugandan
government to effectively check corruption before they could
release any more donations into the country' coffers. One third of
Uganda's government spending comes from donations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
