<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Senior Official Visits Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 1 (Xinhua) -- General Ruppert Smith, deputy
supreme allied commander of Europe, Thursday visited Romania for a
few hours, as part of a tour of countries neighboring the Kosovo
conflict in order to assess the way how they have backed the NATO
efforts.
</P>
<P>
He had an interview at the Cotroceni Palace with presidential
military aide Dorin Marian. General Smith had met earlier Romanian
Defense Minister Victor Babiuc, general Constantin Degeratu, Chief
of Staff of the Romanian Army, and Elena Zamfirescu, Romanian
Foreign Ministry state secretary.
</P>
<P>
General Smith's visit to Romania was part of the constant
dialogue between Romania and the North-Atlantic Alliance, which
has grown more intense with the beginning of the crisis in Kosovo,
Dorin Marian said, adding that there were permanent contacts now
between Romanian political and military decision makers and the
NATO Headquarters,
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of general Smith's visit, the presidential
aide added, was to inform, at the highest level, about the actions
unfolded by the NATO as part of the Resolute Force Operation and
to give assurances that the Alliance most sincerely appreciated
Romania's clear and steady stand.
</P>
<P>
General Smith told the press that during his visit to Romania
he was able to listen to the Romanian authorities' views on Kosovo
issues. He appreciated both the Romanian President's declarations
and the Parliament's Statement, which, he said, clearly set forth
the Romanian state's stand, consistent with Romania's pro-NATO
option. 
</P>
</TEXT>
