<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Troops to Withdraw from Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The bulk of the 1,200
peacekeeping troops of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) in Lesotho are to be withdrawn, South African national
television reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South African Defense Minister Joe Modise said Thursday that
most of the troops would be moved out now that the situation in
Lesotho was stable. But he said a small contingent of instructors
would remain in Lesotho until the country's defense force has been
completely rebuilt and able to function.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Botswana sent their troops to the tiny
mountain kingdom last September to quell an unrest following the
country's general elections in May.
</P>
<P>
Modise said a phased withdrawal would be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Botswana said earlier this week that it would pull out its 378
soldiers by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Botswana Defense Force colonel Jimmi Masisi, the acting
commanding officer of the SADC operation, said both South African
and Botswanan troops would be withdrawn, leaving only a small
force in Lesotho to monitor the run-up to the elections next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Basotho National Party (BNP), a major opposition
party in Lesotho, has welcomed Botswana's plan to pull out troops
and encouraged South Africa to follow suit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
