<HEADLINE> Palestinian Statehood Under Consultation: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
said Thursday the Palestinians are still consulting with friendly
countries on the possible declaration of a Palestinian state on
May 4.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of declaring the Palestinian state is still a point
of discussion with Palestinians' friends and brothers," Arafat
said after a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the
Sinai resort of Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in the Red Sea resort town earlier in the day to
brief Mubarak on his tour of Europe and the U.S.. The tour was
intended to drum up support for the Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has hinted declaration of a state on May 4 when the
five-year interim self-rule period envisaged in the Oslo Accord
signed with Israel in 1993 expires.
</P>
<P>
Several countries have reportedly advised Arafat to postpone
the declaration to a later date to avoid complicating the already
troubled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's political advisor Osman el-Baz, who attended the
meeting, told reporters that Egypt supports whatever the
Palestinians decide on the issue of declaring a state.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to put the issue before the 125-member
Palestinian Central Council at the end of April to make a final
decision.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Central Council is an intermediate body between
the Palestine Liberation Organization's Executive Committee and the
Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader is in Egypt as part of a world tour,
which will also take him to Japan, China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has threatened to
take tough actions against the Palestinian possible step,
including annexation of parts of the West Bank still under
Israel's control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
