<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases Decrease Markedly in Uganda: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said here Thursday that the incidence of AIDS has decreased from
30 percent to 12 percent among pregnant women over the past 10
years in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
This decrease was attributed to the open sensitization policy
by the Ugandan government.
</P>
<P>
Museveni pointed out that to further combat HIV/AIDS, the real
solution now lies in the reactivation and modernization of a
comprehensive family code.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the strengthening of the clan system in
order to handle the problem of orphans, who constitute nearly 10
percent of the total population and are looked after by their
relatives according to the clan system.
</P>
<P>
He said this when meeting with visiting U.S. senior advisor on
HIV/AIDS at the White House, Sandy Thurman, who led a 20-strong
U.S. delegation.
</P>
<P>
Thurman said that Uganda has set a good example in the world in
 combating AIDS. She also praised the country's achievement in
this field.
</P>
<P>
The American delegation arrived in Uganda earlier this week to
assess the support required for community programs that are aimed
at benefiting children orphaned by HIV/AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
