<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloned Sheep Dolly Becomes Mum Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Dolly the sheep, the first mammal
cloned from an adult cell, has been mum again with the birth of
three lambs, its creators announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both Dolly and her three new children, two males and one
female, were doing well, the Roslin Institute in Scotland said.
</P>
<P>
The three lambs, born on March 24, was Dolly's second
pregnancy. Her first lamb, Bonnie, was born last April after Dolly
was mated with a Welsh mountain ram called David, who is also the
father of the three new lambs.
</P>
<P>
Dolly was born in July 1996 at the Roslin Institute after
scientists inserted a cell from a ewe's udder into an egg after
removing the egg's DNA.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have believed that it is important to breed from
cloned animals to check for any unexpected changes in their
offspring.
</P>
<P>
"The birth of Bonnie almost exactly 12 months ago confirmed
that despite Dolly's unusual origins she is able to breed normally
and produce healthy offspring," said Dr Harry Griffin, the
assistant director of the institute, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The birth of these three lambs is further demonstration of
this," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Millers Urged to Withdraw Flour Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Industry and Commerce
Minister Nathan Shamuyarira Thursday said the recent 20 percent
increase in the price of flour by millers was not acceptable to
the government.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Harare, the minister said
millers should withdraw the increases within the next seven days
or the government will gazette the prices to acceptable levels.
</P>
<P>
He said bread was now a basic need of Zimbabweans and it should
be affordable to ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
"I am making a final appeal to millers to withdraw the
increases so that bread becomes affordable to everyone," he said.
</P>
<P>
Millers have said the increase was necessary to offset high
input costs.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the basic commodities raised prices of
about 60 percent in the past three months. The Zimbabweans urged
the government to control prices of all basic commodities.
</P>
</TEXT>
