<HEADLINE> U.S., NATO Confirm Capture of U.S. Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and NATO officials
confirmed Thursday that three American soldiers were captured near
the Yugoslav-Macedonia border following a skirmish with Yugoslav
troops.
</P>
<P>
Capt. John Clearwater, spokesman for the U.S. Army's 1st
Infantry Division in Germany, said that the three U.S. soldiers
from his unit, who had lost contact for several hours after being
attacked by unknown troops, "are alive and well and appear
healthy."
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav Television showed the three American soldiers,
saying that they were captured within the border of Yugoslavia
when on a reconnaissance mission.
</P>
<P>
"We've seen the pictures on television, we don't like it," said
U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the command of NATO forces. "We're
still investigating where the incident occurred," Clark told a
press conference at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
NATO and U.S. officials said earlier that the three came under
fire and surrendered shortly before losing radio contact about
three miles inside Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
At the same press conference, NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana alleged that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic would be
held "personally responsible" for the safety of the three American
soldiers. This message, he added, has already been sent to
Yugoslavia through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Yugoslavia, severely defying the air
bombing of U.S.-led NATO forces for more than a week, has shot
down dozens of NATO missiles and airplanes, including an advanced
F-117A stealth fighter Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
