<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Measures on Jerusalem Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 1 (Xinhua)-- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Thursday sharply criticized a Israeli decision on
closing Palestinian institutions in East Jerusalem, saying it was
nothing but aggressive measures against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Gaza, the PNA said "the Israeli
decision was a challenge to international legitimacy," stressing
that "Jerusalem forms a red line that can not be overridden," the
Voice of Palestine reported.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Israel decided to close three Palestinian offices,
including the office of the Palestinian News Agency, in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
But Faisal Husseini, minister of the Jerusalem Affairs of the
PNA, pointed out on the same day that no matter what happens, the
Orient House, the de facto office of the PNA, and other offices in
East Jerusalem will function as usual and remain open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken apparently due to the increased
palestinian political and diplomatic activities in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Last week, foreign diplomats in Jerusalem were invited to a
meeting in the Orient House to be briefed on the current situation
in the Mideast peace process despite Israel's strong objections.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, diplomats of the European Union (EU) member states
in Jerusalem were once more invited to the Orient House and the
Palestinian officials expressed their gratitude for the EU's
support for their right of self-determination in declaring an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has threatened to declared an independent state on May
4 when the five-year interim Palestinian self-rule expires
according to the 1993 Oslo Accord. The EU supports the
Palestinians' right on the statehood.
</P>
<P>
The EU also rejects Israel's claim that Jerusalem is its
eternal capital, saying the fate of Jerusalem should be settled in
the final status talks in line with the Oslo Accord.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks, which have yet to start, should have
begun by May in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
