<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Says Basis for Agreement Reached in N.Irish Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said Thursday that Northern Ireland's talks on disarmament were
adjourned to April 13 but politicians had reached a "basis for
agreement."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference with the Irish Taoiseach
Bertie Ahern at Hillsborough Castle after three days of talks,
Blair said both governments were convinced they would get full
agreement from all parties in favor of a "declaration" setting out
a timescale for establishing the Northern Ireland Assembly's
executive and the decommissioning of weapons.
</P>
<P>
"There is no turning back on the road to peace," he said,
adding the latest agreement was another "huge and significant
milestone."
</P>
<P>
Blair described the three-day talks as being about dialogue and
leaving the past behind.
</P>
<P>
"One year on we can be proud to say it is clear that all of the
parties are wedded to the Good Friday Agreement."
</P>
<P>
He also said the adjournment was now a "short pause for
reflection."
</P>
<P>
He said that the government would publish a declaration which
would allow the institutions in the agreement, the ruling
executive, the North-South Council, the cross-border bodies and
the British-Irish Council to be put in place within the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock sprang from the refusal of the Ulster Unionists to
allow Sinn Fein to take up its seats in the Northern Ireland
Assembly executive without a start to IRA disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams expressed disappointment that
the deadline of setting up the provincial executive had been
missed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
