<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Shines on Opening Day at World Short-Course Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Swimming powerhouse Australia
stole the limelight on the opening day of the four-day World
Short-Course Swimming Championships by taking three out of nine
golds Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Australia's teenager Ian Thorpe, 16, set the first world record
of the tournament when he won the men's 200 meters freestyle with
a time of 1:43.28, shaving 0.36 of a second off the previous mark
of 1:43.64 clocked by Georgio Lamberti of Italy in Bonn in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish women's relay team stormed to a world record in the
4x200 meters freestyle relay, clocking in 7:51.70 to beat the
previous mark of 7:51.92 created by the Chinese in Gothenborg in
1997.
</P>
<P>
"It's my second short course world record, I've learn to accept
that," Thorpe said.
</P>
<P>
"It's not difficult, you have to get on with your career. Don't
let that stand in your way," added Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe and the Swedish team pocketed 15,000 U.S. dollars given
by FINA, the international swimming governing body, for their
setting world records.
</P>
<P>
The Australian men's team including Thorpe and Michael Klim won
the 4x100 meters relay title in 3 minutes 11.21 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Australia's world record holder Matthew Dunn took the third
title for their courtry and smashed the meeting's record in the
men's 400m medley, clocking in 4 minutes 06.05 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Masami Tanaka beat world record holder Han Xue of China
and won the only gold for Asian when she clocked 30.80 in the
women's 50m breaststroke, just 0.03 seconds off Han's world mark
set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Penny Heyns of South Africa came second in 30.
88 and Han Xue third in 31.24.
</P>
<P>
The Ukraines took two golds when Yana Klochkova and Dmytro
Krayeskyy triumphed in the women's 400m medley with a time of 4:32.
32 and the men's 50m breaststroke in time of 27.40 seconds
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Other winners Thursday are Cuba's Rodolfo Falcon, who set the
tournament record and won the men's 50-meter backstroke in 24.34
seconds, and Denmark's Mette Jacobsen who took the women's 200m
butterfly in 2:06.52.
</P>
<P>
China, a favorite in the tournament, cliched only one bronze
medal by Han Xue in the women's 50m breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
"Many of Our team are effected by flu and most of them are not
in top form now. Hopefully they can recover in the coming year, "
said the chinese coach Lu Yongming.
</P>
<P>
China's winning hope is Chen Hua, who are unbeaten in this
season's world cup short course series in the women's 400m and 800
m freestyle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0028 </DOCNO>
