<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International migration Organization Moves out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Organization for
Migration decided Thursday to close its office in Luanda, capital
of Angola, for sheer financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
Mario Tavolla, representative of the migration organization to
Luanda, said that the deficit-ridden organization was forced to
make the decision after it received no response from the
international society for its Angolan aid call.
</P>
<P>
Tavolla said that leaders of the organization toured the
southern African country recently and decided that its office in
South Africa will cover its affairs in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Though the office in Luanda is closed, the representative said,
the organization will continue its current programs and will
develop new programs in the future.
</P>
<P>
International Organization for Migration was established in
1951, aimed at facilitating the legal migration of people across
the world, offering necessary help to refugees and displaced. The
organization entered Angola in 1997 to help repatriate the war
refugees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Changes Lending Rates on Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) Thursday announced changes in its lending rates on the
convertible-currency portion of loans from ordinary capital for
the first semester of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based bank also introduced a euro rate to its
menu of single currency loans. The euro became the successor
currency to the German mark and 10 other national currencies in
Europe on January 1.
</P>
<P>
For outstanding balances of currency-pool adjustable rate loans
approved after January 1, 1999, the annual lending rate is 6.64
percent in the first half of 1999, compared with 6.68 percent in
the second semester of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The lending rate applicable to outstanding balances of
adjustable rate loans in U.S. dollars from the single currency
facility (SCF) remains unchanged at 6.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
The euro SCF rate for the first semester 1999 is 5.38 percent
compared with the German mark SCF rate of 5.94 percent in the
second semester of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The rate for loans in Japanese yen in the first semester 1999
is 2.11 percent, compared with 2.61 percent in the second semester
of 1998. The new SCF rate for loans in Swiss francs is 3.88
percent, compared with 4.07 percent in the second semester of
1998.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that full credit fee of 0.75 percent will be
charged on all signed undisbursed loans during the first semester
of 1999 compared with the reduced fee of 0.25 percent charged
during the second semester of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 1 percent full inspection fee, which was waived during the
the second semester of 1998, will be charged duing the first
semester 1999, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0031 </DOCNO>
