<HEADLINE> Greece Opens Air Space for Turkish Cargo Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Air Force Commander Ilhan
Kilic said on Thursday Greece has opened its air space to Turkish
cargo planes carrying humanitarian aid to Albania.
</P>
<P>
Anatolia News Agency quoted Kilic as saying in the central
province of Kayseri that "our three cargo planes left Turkey for
Tirana Wednesday and another cargo plane would leave today."
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Greece opened its air space to
Turkish cargo planes, he said, adding "our planes brought 36
tonnes of food and medicine of Red Crescent to Albania."
</P>
<P>
"We don't have any difficulty in transportation of aid to
Tirana," said the commander, adding that as long as the Red
Crescent wishes, the Turkish cargo planes will continue to
transport humanitarian aid and Greece doesn't cause any difficulty
regarding this issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey's Red Crescent has also sent 11 trucks of
humanitarian aid to Albania and Macedonia, where tens of thousands
of Kosovo Albanian refugees have poured in since the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization launched air strikes on Yugoslavia on
March 24. 
</P>
