<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Holds Dinosaur Exhibition in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese dinosaur museum is
holding a unique dinosaur exhibition in Johannesburg, South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
On display are eight complete dinosaur fossil skeletons and
about 90 pieces of fossil specimens of dinosaurs and other
animals.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is the first ever of its kind in South Africa
and is expected to attract quite a lot of visitors, said Hilary
Bruce, director of Museum Africa, where the display is being held.
</P>
<P>
All the articles are from Zigong Dinosaur Museum of Sichuan,
China, the biggest in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The fossils of the dinosaurs on display, which lived in the
middle of the Jurassic Period, are rare in other parts of the
world, according to Peng Guangzhao, deputy director of the Zigong
Dinosaur Museum.
</P>
<P>
At an opening ceremony Thursday afternoon, Chairman of South
Africa's National Arts Council, John Kani, said the exhibition has
special significance to Africans as Africans did not record their
history in writing. Such exhibitions, therefore, can be very
informative and educational, he said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, which is part of the Sino-South African
cultural exchange program, will run until July 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most COMESA Members Favor Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen of the 21-member
countries of the Common Market For Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) have so far ratified the treaty in favor of a free trade
area by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
COMESA Secretary General Erastus Mwencha disclosed this when
he received Zimbabwe's ratification of the COMESA treaty in Lusaka
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said Angola, Namibia and Swaziland are the only
countries that have not yet ratified the treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said the three countries are actively persuing the process
of ratification.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha added that it has given the regional group the
confidence of establishing a free trade area in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He added that COMESA exports now amount to 62 billion U.S.
dollars while intra-COMESA trade is at three billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
