<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria '99, First FIFA Competition in Sub-Saharan Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The 10th World Youth Championship (
WYC) will be held from April 3 to 24 in Nigeria and this is the
first time that a FIFA (Federation of International Football
Association) competition has been hosted by a country in Sub-
Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The U-20 WYC tagged Nigeria '99 is also the first time for
Nigeria to host such an international football championship in
which 24 teams all over the world will participate.
</P>
<P>
Nigerians were originally scheduled to run the 1995 event, but
medical considerations made it necessary to alter the venue that
year with Qatar springing in to fill the gap at short notice.
</P>
<P>
Although the local organizing committee of Nigeria has no
experience of running a major event of this calibre with worldwide
interest, they are very active in their efforts to make sure
things run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has also made funds available for
bringing facilities in eight venues in the most populous African
country up to the required level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the host country of Nigeria must be counted among
the favourites who will compete for the coveted WYC trophy for
1999.
</P>
<P>
Their best achievement so far was winning the Olympic Football
tournament in 1996 by the national A team called "Super Eagles"
which have also performed well at continental level and on their
appearances in the World Cup finals rounds in 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the U-20 category, no African team has ever made it right to
the top, but Nigeria reached the final in 1989 and Ghana also took
silver in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Of the eight U-17 world championships held so far, African
teams have won on four occasions, that is, Nigeria in 1985 and
1993 and Ghana in 1991 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
The countries which top the list are Brazil and Argentina with
three wins each at the WYC, and Argentina, champions in 1995 in
Qatar and 1997 in Malaysia will be going for a record of three
titles in a row.
</P>
<P>
The main obstacles to further South American success will come
from Europe in the form of 1981 champions Germany and double
winners Portugal (1989 and 1991) as well as from Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Asian teams will be hoping to improve on past performances,
and this time their contingent includes a newcomer to the
competition in the shape of Kazakhstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
