<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Defends Policy Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) Javier Solana Thursday defended the
19-nation alliance's aggression policy in Yugoslavia, saying
NATO's cause "is a just one."
</P>
<P>
Solana told reporters here that NATO tried to achieve political
goals through negotiations, but Yugoslav leader rejected the
Rambouillet agreement. NATO heads had time and again repeated as
such recently.
</P>
<P>
"He left the alliance no other option but to start military
operations," the NATO chief said, indicating the West could not
find any other way to deal with the Kosovo crisis, but only war
against Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav leader. NATO has always
said it is not at war with the Yugoslav people but their leader.
</P>
<P>
"NATO will stop only when he stops," Solana told reporters at
the Brussels-based NATO headquarters when he and NATO Supreme
Commander Wesley Clark were briefing assessment on NATO attacks in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"NATO has begun a difficult operation. But we believe that it
is the right thing to do, and that it is our duty to do whatever
we can to stop the killing in Kosovo," he said.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's chief said the ring is closing around the
Yugoslav armed forces. "The impact of our air campaign will be
increasingly cumulative. This is an effective operation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Solana also defended NATO's bombing in Kosovo which some
observers hold has created humanitarian disaster after a crowd of
refugees fled into neighboring countries. "There is only one
person responsible for all of the refugees now flowing into the
neighboring countries, and that is Milosevic."
</P>
<P>
"Every refugee testifies that Milosevic's soldiers drove them
from their homes, not NATO bombs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO leader of the aggression forces in Yugoslavia also
warned the Yugoslav leader that as NATO pressure increases, "he
will be forced to stop his aggression."
</P>
<P>
The NATO air attack operation in Yugoslavia entered into the
eighth day Thursday, but it did not make much progress because of
the strong defensive system of Yugoslav forces and what NATO
termed as unfavorable weather. Therefore, Solana said the NATO
attack "is not a situation that can be resolved in 24 or 48
hours." "We will be successful but we need stamina and
determination," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
