<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Hospital Shows Wounded Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Ivan Tanasijevic, 14, lies in the
intensive care unit of the Clinical Center of Serbia in central
Belgrade, with catheters in his mouth and nostrils and a
ventilator beside him.
</P>
<P>
Ivan, a Bosnian refugee, was admitted to the Clinical Center of
Serbia in a comma with a fractured scull, brain hemorrhage. He was
hit by bricks and debris after his house collapsed in NATO
bombardment Wednesday in Loznitsa, said Vlada Vostic, a doctor
with the center's neurology department.
</P>
<P>
Losnitsa, located near the Serbian border with Bosnia, is 150
kilometers southwest of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Ivan was one of the seven civilians severely wounded in NATO
bombings on Yugoslavia, which entered its ninth day Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dobrica Vukojicic, a 46-year-old farmer, was wounded Wednesday
when NATO launched air raids on Kraljevo, a city 160 kilometers
south of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Dejan Lukic, 13, was also wounded in Loznitsa. His whole right
leg was bondaged. A catheter was attached to his urethra.
</P>
<P>
Besides physiological damage, the civilian population were
under severe psychological pressure.
</P>
<P>
Boris Grubichic, 18, jumped from the top floor of the
McDonald's in central Belgrade on March 24, the first night of
NATO's bombing campaign. He died in the clinical center in the
previous day, the head nurse told about a dozen foreign reporters.
</P>
<P>
With news that NATO was planning to bomb government agencies,
doctors, nurses and patients were under increasing panic, as an
army headquarters is only across the street from the department of
neurology and another clinic is only about 100 meters from the
Interior Ministry, Vostic said.
</P>
<P>
Many of the patients, including those with cancer, have gone
home, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to understand that you can establish a new world
order or help someone by bombing," Vostic said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
