<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Spending Posts Strong Growth in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Americans' spending on goods
and services jumped a seasonally adjusted 0.7 percent in February,
after a 0.4 percent rise in January, the Commerce Department said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Personal income also showed a robust growth at a seasonally
adjusted 0.5 percent in February following a 0.6 percent gain in
January. As Americans' spending outpaced income in February, the
nation's savings rate was dragged into the negative territory
again.
</P>
<P>
Both figures were expected by analysts and illustrate the
strength of the U.S. economy during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Income growth has been supported by rising wages, up 0.7
percent in February. Demand for labor is strong, with the nation's
unemployment rate hovering near a 29-year low.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting that, the Labor Department reported Thursday that
first-time claims for unemployment benefits fell by 6,000 to
289,000 last week. The claims have kept under 300,000 for nine
weeks in a row, a stretch unprecedented since 1973.
</P>
<P>
Americans' spending, however, has been supported by more than
job income. They're spending some of their stock market gains and
tapping into their home equity through refinancing.
</P>
<P>
That's produced the lowest personal savings rate -- savings as
a percentage of after-tax income -- since the 1930s. It was minus
0.2 percent in February, the fifth month in six at or below zero.
</P>
<P>
In addition to wages, other income categories increasing were
business owners' income, transfer payments such as Social
Security, interest and dividends and rental income. Farmers'
income, however, fell.
</P>
<P>
Spending was led by a 2.9 percent jump in purchases of durable
goods, big-ticket items expected to last three or more years. Much
of that was for autos. Spending rose 0.6 percent for nondurable
goods such as food and fuel and 0.3 percent for services.
</P>
<P>
In another sign of economic vigor, the Commerce Department
reported separately that construction spending jumped a
much-stronger-than-expected 2.2 percent in February, the largest
increase in eight months and the fourth in a row.
</P>
<P>
Construction spending was led by a 4.7 percent surge in
government projects, reflecting a 10.4 percent increase for
highways and streets.
</P>
<P>
Commercial construction increased 3.9 percent, with gains in
industrial projects, office buildings and retail stores.
Residential construction rose 0.8 percent, including a 1.5 percent
advance for single-family homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
