<HEADLINE> Russian Warships' Entrance to Mediterranean Will </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said here on Thursday the passage of Russian warships
through Turkish straits to the Mediterranean Sea or the Adriatic
Sea would recover the morale of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit told reporters that the deployment of the Russian
warships to the region might also embolden Belgrade to kill
ethnic Albanians in the warring Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Russian warships would be carrying
out "reconnaissance tasks" in the war zone "because of the
ongoing situation in Yugoslavia," which has been under air attacks
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization since March 24 for its
refusal to sign a peace deal with the separatist Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has given the green light to a Russian
naval squadron to pass through the Canakkale and Bosphorus
Straits linking the Black Sea to the Mediterranean Sea between
April 3 and 8.
</P>
<P>
The Russian embassy in Ankara has presented two requests for
the passage of eight Russian warships through its straits.
</P>
<P>
The fleet will include a missile carrier, anti-submarine
frigates and other escort vessels from the Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
The passage of foreign warships through the Turkish straits
is overseen by the 1936 Treaty of Montreux.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Black Sea littoral states can sail
their ships through the straits if they inform the Turkish
authorities of their intentions at least eight days in advance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
