<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Government Regulates Commuter Taxis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Transport Licensing Board
will regulate all matatus (commuter taxis) operating in the
country and matatu touts will no longer be allowed to mill around
terminuses, a local source said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Francis ole Sompisha, head of the board, said that city and
local councils across the country will manage all bus and matatu
terminuses and device a method of getting revenue for improving
and maintaining the terminus facilities.
</P>
<P>
Matatu and bus owners will be free from now on to hire drivers
and conductors of their choice and give them badges obtained from
the Registrar of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Sompisha said that these were some of the new measures
announced Thursday to end the reign of self-appointed syndicates
controlling the matatu business, adding that his board has assumed
sole authority to allot routes to matatus and buses.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that these measures to be taken by his board are
to ensure safety and to harmonize the country's transport as the
matatu operators are often ignorant of the traffic rules and cause
many road accidents by speeding or stopping at wrong places.
</P>
<P>
The move requires that drivers and conductors must have
identification badges issued by the Registrar of Motor Vehicles,
and they must apply for licenses to operate public service
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The official said his board had consulted Philemon Abong'o,
Police Commissioner of Kenya, over the implementation of the new
system. He said no driver or conductor would be allowed to
operate without a license.
</P>
<P>
The Transport Licensing Board, established in 1957, consists of
a chairman appointed by the state president, and eight other
members appointed by the minister for transport to represent each
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
