<HEADLINE> Japan's 152 Local Assemblies Oppose Guideline Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Japan's 152 local assemblies have
adopted resolutions opposing a set of bills aimed at implementing
the revised Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines, a survey
released Friday said.
</P>
<P>
Kyodo News said the survey, conducted by a group opposed to the
bills, showed that as of Thursday, one prefectural assembly and
151 municipal assemblies in 30 of Japan's 47 prefectures expressed
opposition to the bills or misgivings about them.
</P>
<P>
The bills are currently being deliberated in the Diet (
parliament), with the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) eager
to get them enacted.
</P>
<P>
Shizuoka Prefectural Assembly said in its resolution that the
guidelines would have a significant impact on inhabitants' lives
and economic activity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a 10,000-strong union of private university teachers
in Tokyo issued a statement Friday expressing opposition to the
bills.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the guidelines could draw Japan into wars, and that
they will effectively change the current Japan-U.S. security
treaty for the worse, the union urged the Japanese central
government scrap the bills,
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Japan and the United States updated the defense
guidelines which would allow Japan's Self-Defense Forces (SDF) to
provide rear-area logistical support to U.S. forces and to conduct
search and rescue operations during emergencies in unspecified "
areas surrounding Japan."
</P>
<P>
The bills also affect Japanese local governments by requiring
them to allow U.S. forces to use ports and airports under their
control and to accept injured at local hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
