<HEADLINE> Dog Is Wet-Nurse To Five Lion Cubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Five newborn lion cubs in the
north China city of Shijiazhuang are being wet-nursed by a dog
because their mother has insufficient milk.
</P>
<P>
The dog was chosen from among some 20 candidates before the
mother lion in the city's zoo gave the birth on Thursday,
according to zookeeper Wang Wanhua.
</P>
<P>
"The dog lost her own baby just three days ago, maybe that's
the reason why she looks rather maternal to the lion cubs," Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
The six-year old mother lion, "Xinxin." is unable to produce
enough milk even though she has given birth to eleven other cubs.
But those cubs were fed with artificial food and became ill
because of weak immune systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
The zookeepers, who decided dog milk would be suitable for lion
cubs, started to look for a wet-nurse dog through the local media
soon after "Xinxin" became pregnant. More than 20 people responded
recommending their dogs, before one was finally selected.
</P>
</TEXT>
