<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Falls to 29-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The nationwide unemployment
rate in the United States dropped to a new 29-year low of 4.2
percent in March despite continued job losses in manufacturing and
sluggish job growth elsewhere, the Labor Department reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted rate, based on a survey of households,
fell from 4.4 percent in February and was the lowest since
February 1970, when the rate was also 4.2 percent
</P>
<P>
However, a separate survey showed employers added just 46,000
jobs in March to their payrolls, in contrast to 297,000 jobs in
February and 217,000 in January. It was the smallest number since
jobs declined in January 1996 when a blizzard struck the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers, many hit hard by the global economic slump that
began in Asia near two years ago, cut 35,000 jobs last month,
bringing the decline for the past year to 381,000.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, losses have been most severe at factories
making industrial machinery, apparel and electrical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Construction hiring fell by a seasonally adjusted 47,000 jobs
in March after the actual gain in jobs fell short of the normal
advance for the start of spring.
</P>
<P>
Mining, which includes oil-drilling, lost 7,000 jobs in March,
bringing losses over the past year to 55,000. Agricultural
services and real estate also recorded declines.
</P>
<P>
However, robust employment growth continued in engineering and
management services, health care, educational services and
amusement and recreation. There also were gains in computer and
data processing and finance and insurance.
</P>
<P>
By demographic group, the jobless rate for Hispanics fell from
6.7 percent in February to 5.8 percent, the lowest on record since
the Labor Department began calculating a separate rate for the
group in 1973.
</P>
<P>
The rate fell from 3.8 percent to 3.6 percent for whites, from
8.3 percent to 8.1 percent for blacks and from 3.7 percent to 3.2
percent for men. It rose from 3.8 percent to 3.9 percent for women
and from 14.1 percent to 14.3 percent for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
The rate for adults who dropped out of high school fell from
7.5 percent to 6.1 percent. For high school graduates it was
unchanged at 3.4 percent and, for college graduates, unchanged at
1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Average hourly earnings for non-farm, non-supervisory workers
rose 3 cents in March to 13.09 U.S. dollars. They're up 3.6
percent from a year earlier. The average workweek declined by a
tenth of an hour to 34.5 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
