<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Seizes Pirated VCDs worth HK$1 m </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Customs officers
seized a huge batch of pirated Video Compact Discs (VCDs)
estimated at a value of about one million HK dollars (about 128,
200 U.S. dollars) in a latest operation, government sources said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
After a two-week-long investigation, Customs officers raided an
optical disc packaging and storage center on Thursday night,
capturing 60,000 pirated VCDs and arresting four suspects.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Customs and Excise Department said Friday
that the department would continue to take vigorous enforcement
action against piracy activities including those involving retail
shops on the street during Easter and the traditional Tomb
Sweeping holidays, which start Friday and end next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The on-going anti-piracy operations demonstrate our
determination in combating piracy activities and preserving the
good image of Hong Kong," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Since the operation, code-named "Thunderbolt", started in mid-
March this year, Hong Kong Customs officers have raided 207 shops,
seized 800,000 pirated optical discs, worth 17 million HK dollars
(about 2.2 million U.S. dollars) and arrested 124 suspects.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of this year, the Customs seized 2.16
million pirated optical discs with a market value of 39 million HK
dollars (about five million U.S. dollars), and arrested 288 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
