<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Open Its Telecom Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China will further open its
telecommunications market by conducting an experimental
introduction of foreign funds into the telecom operations of the
Pudong New Area in Shanghai, said Wu Jichuan, minister of
Information Industry (MII), at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Posts and Telecommunications Administrative Bureau
signed an agreement with AT&AMP;T on March 31 to jointly handle
telecom services in Pudong, making AT&AMP;T the first foreign company
to enter this sector in China.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be submitted to the State Council for
approval and will become effective nine months after the approval,
said Wu, who called this a "breakthrough" on the way to opening up
the country's telecom sector.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the MII will intensify management of the
domestic market to help national telecom enterprises upgrade their
competitive position in the world market, according to Wu.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the country currently has about 2,900
telecom service companies, including China Telecom and China
Unicom, and many Internet service providers (ISP) and Internet
content providers (ICP).
</P>
<P>
Wu also encouraged China's telecom sector to accelerate the
absorption of advanced foreign techniques, and improve China's own
technology.
</P>
<P>
China's telecom industry began manufacturing program-controlled
switchboards for telephones in 1982, and their products now occupy
98 percent of the domestic market, and are also exported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
