<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Volunteers Plant Trees in Xiandu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIANDU (Zhejiang), April 2 (Xinhua) -- The members of the `99
China International Young Volunteers Camp today added beauty to
the landscape by planting trees in Xiandu in east China's Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day camp, the fourth of its kind ever held in China,
focuses on environmental protection and cultural exchange, with
young volunteers from a number of countries, including Japan,
Britain, Australia, the Republic of Korea and Canada attending the
camp along with Chinese youth.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 campers worked hard digging holes, carrying soil
and planting two-meter-high cypresses. "I never imagined that I
would have the opportunity to plant trees in Xiandu," said Marcela
Kraemerova, from the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Marcela, the youngest camper among the foreign volunteers, also
said she was very happy to do some work for environmental
protection in Xiandu.
</P>
<P>
Gavin Starks from Scotland did his planting quickly. "This is
easier than I did before," said Starks, who has been to other work
camps both in Scotland and abroad.
</P>
<P>
In the days to come, the campers will repair roads and provide
many kinds of voluntary services to the local communities, and
conduct exchanges with the local students.
</P>
<P>
The International Young Volunteers Camp was started by
youngsters from Germany and France in the 1920s as part of an
effort to rehabilitate farms and pastures destroyed during the
First World War.  
</P>
</TEXT>
