<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Defends Government Position on Yugoslav </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides on Friday described the government's position on the
Yugoslav crisis as "balanced, taking into consideration Cyprus'
interests".
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides made the remarks when he was briefing Cyprus' party
leaders or representatives on the government position regarding
the Yugoslav crisis.
</P>
<P>
House (Parliament) President Spyros Kyprianou had announced
that Cyprus would organize an all party rally on Saturday to
condemn the continuing air strikes by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Later Friday, the House plenary is expected to approve a
petition condemning the bombings in Yugoslavia and calling for a
political settlement to the problem.
</P>
<P>
But the Government Spokesman Costas Serezis on Friday told the
reporters that the government will not participate in the all
party rally, and at the same time it is not trying to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister explained to the party representatives
that Cyprus must take into consideration its European Union (EU)
accession course.
</P>
<P>
The NATO started the air strikes on March 24 after
West-brokered peace talks between the Belgrade government and the
separatist ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province collapsed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
