<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Antarctic Expedition Returns to Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese ship Xuelong (Snow
Dragon) docked at the port of Shanghai today, marking the
successful conclusion of its scientific expedition to the South
Pole.
</P>
<P>
The Xuelong departed Shanghai on November 5 last year,
embarking on China's 15th expedition to the Antarctic continent
since the first expedition was mounted in 1984. The Xuelong sailed
20,326 nautical miles over a period of 149 days to reach its
destination.
</P>
<P>
Members of the expedition conducted scientific research and
environmental protection activities, including the collection of
more than 200 tons of waste and rubbish which were shipping back
for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Significant progress was made toward the realization of
research goals outlined in China's 1996-2000 Guidelines for
Antarctic Research. The team's studies of the Antarctic ice cover
not only will provide a deeper understanding of the laws of global
climate changes, but will also greatly enhance the ability to
predict future changes.
</P>
<P>
The team of explorers traveled 1,100 kilometers toward the
polar ice cap, reaching the pole's highest point, and drilled rich
and varied ice samples.
</P>
<P>
The team also went to Grove Mountains where they found four
meteorites and a place to anchor their ship on the southeastern
portion of the pole.
</P>
<P>
An airport currently being built jointly by China, Russia, and
Australia in the ice-covered region is well under way, and is
scheduled to be completed at the beginning of the next century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
