<HEADLINE> Nigeria's First Bank Withdraws from Ticket Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The First Bank of Nigeria, official
banker of the 10th World Youth Championship (WYC), has withdrawn
from the agreement to sell tickets of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
The bank pulled out of the earlier arrangement on Thursday
evening because of the incompetence of the Local Organizing
Committee (LOC) which had not delivered the tickets for sale less
than 48 hours to kick off the championship tagged Nigeria '99.
</P>
<P>
In a news release, the bank said that the LOC was supposed to
have delivered the tickets to its head office since January 31 for
ware-housing and subsequent distribution to agents accredited by
the LOC in all the designated eight venues.
</P>
<P>
The tickets, as at 5 p.m. on April 1, have not been delivered,
thus negating all the arrangements made by the bank to mobilize
resources in readiness for the distribution, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The LOC has also not provided the bank with a list of its
accredited agents to whom distribution should be made in various
zones, it added.
</P>
<P>
Given the above scenario, the release said, the First Bank of
Nigeria has not been placed in a position to render the necessary
logistical support for effective distribution of the gate tickets.
</P>
<P>
This development has left anxious Nigerians and indeed, those
of the participating countries in a quandary, local newspapers
said Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
