<HEADLINE> Scattering Ashes into Sea Popular in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Today is China's Tomb Sweeping
Festival, and the ashes of 80 deceased people of the city of
Fuzhou in east China were scattered into the sea by their
relatives.
</P>
<P>
This activity, sponsored by the city's bureau of civil affairs,
was the third such in Fuzhou.
</P>
<P>
Yang Wenji, 74, accompanied by his wife, scattered the ashes of
his mother, which he had kept for the past 60 years, into the sea.
"I hope my mother has eternal life in the sea," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Haiyuan, director of the city's funeral and interment
management office, said that when the city introduced this
ceremony for the first time in 1997, there were only a few people
willing to scatter the ashes of their relatives into sea.
</P>
<P>
While only four people's ashes were scattered into sea in 1997,
the number soared to 66 in 1998 when the event was held for the
second time.
</P>
<P>
Gao Minfeng, a 62-year-old Fuzhou woman, believes that
scattering ashes is both civil and wise, saying that "when I pass
away, I am willing to be scattered into sea." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Standardizes Overseas-Listed Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China has adopted eleven new
regulations to standardize the operations of the 43 overseas-
listed companies in order to better protect the interests of
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
These regulations, jointly formulated by the State Economic and
Trade Commission (SETC) and the China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), are designated to solve existing problems in
the operations of overseas-listed companies.
</P>
<P>
These follow the five measures CSRC Chairman Zhou Zhengqing
pledged to international investors in London in February.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations require the boards and management of
overseas-listed companies to increase transparency by establishing
and perfecting information-disclosure mechanisms. CSRC has also
drafted a set of rules on information disclosure for these
overseas-listed companies.
</P>
<P>
These rules prohibit government shareholders and their
representatives from bypassing boards of directors and interfering
in the operations of the companies. The rules also require the
separation of operating institutions of the companies from their
holding institutions.
</P>
<P>
The rules also call for further restructuring the companies,
rationalizing decision-making procedures, clarifying
responsibilities of directors, stabilizing senior management,
establishing and perfecting a system of external directors and
independent directors, reinforcing the role of supervisory
committees, adding incentives for senior executives, and
intensifying company reform.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the challenges of a knowledge-based economy,
the companies are also required to make full use of external
consultation sources. The regulations also stipulate that for
major investment projects, the companies should solicit
professional opinions from external consultants to serve as an
important basis for board decisions.
</P>
<P>
Shao Ning, director-general of the Department of Enterprises
Reform under the SETC, noted that defects in standardizing
operations of listed companies has aroused doubts about the
effectiveness of measures taken by China to restructure state-
owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that overseas-listed companies are already
under the strict regulations of international law, and are
therefore seen by the government as vanguards in the country's
drive to adopt international business practices.
</P>
<P>
A CSRC official said that the regulatory institution will adopt
further measures to accelerate upgrading the operations of listed
companies to international standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders Appoint New CIS Executive Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) on Friday agreed to the appointment of
Yury Yarov, a close aide of Russian President Boris Yeltsin, as
executive secretary of the 12-nation grouping.
</P>
<P>
The CIS heads of state reached the agreement at a regular
summit meeting of the CIS, which opened here Thursday, the Itar-
Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yarov, who had been deputy chief of Yeltsin's office since 1996,
was appointed as Yeltsin's representative to the upper house of
the Russian parliament on December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Berezovsky was sacked by Yeltsin on March 5. Yeltsin accused
him of "exceeding the limits of his authority as executive
secretary and failing to implement instructions by the chairman of
the CIS Council."
</P>
<P>
His removal, a unilateral move by Yeltsin, reportedly angered
fellow CIS heads of state.
</P>
<P>
The CIS leaders discussed internal affairs of the group and the
crisis in Yugoslavia and adopted a manifest on the future
development of the CIS, which is comprised of all the republics of
the former Soviet Union except the three Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the summit, Yeltsin said the CIS played an active
role in safeguarding the sovereignty of its member states and
urged the group to prepare for the changing world situation.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said Russia will step up the equal and mutually
beneficial integration process with other CIS members in order to
strengthen relations among the CIS states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
