<HEADLINE> World Bank Meeting Calls for More Transparency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Policy makers from East Asian
countries ended a meeting organized by the World Bank here Friday
after adopting a statement calling for more transparency in the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Financial transactions needed greater transparency through
improved reporting, accounting and auditing, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Attendants agreed that East Asian countries should speed up
restructuring with an expansion of domestic demand so as to ensure
the region's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the necessity of lowering interest rates to
bolster the recovery which they said was starting to emerge in
several nations.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting was aimed at presenting data gathered
from an extensive survey of more than 4,000 small- and
medium-sized firms in the region so that initiatives and viable
policy solutions would be drawn and developed for sustainable
economic growth in the future.
</P>
<P>
The survey results, as well as discussions and exchanged
information in the meeting, would help policy makers in the
countries realize and determine financial status of small- and
medium-sized enterprises in a wide rage of industries, both in
their own country and neighboring trading nations, according to
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also reached the conclusion that stimulation of
domestic demand was not enough to spur recovery and that speedier
restructuring of banks and other financial institutions was vital
to corporate recovery.
</P>
<P>
"Companies must overcome remaining major constraints if
recovery is to be speeded up and sustained," said a World Bank
analysis of the survey.
</P>
<P>
"These results provide another important lesson in that an
expansion of demand alone is not enough to revive the corporate
sector. Corporate restructuring to enhance competitiveness is also
required and those companies carrying it out will be the first to
experience recovery," the analysis said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
