<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Challenge U.S. Over Trade Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada is using the North American
Free-Trade Agreement (NAFTA) to challenge the United States over a
proposed North Dakota law that would restrict exports of Canadian
agricultural products into the country.
</P>
<P>
The challenge was officially launched Thursday as the United
States issued a long list of complaints about its world trade
partners, including Canada.
</P>
<P>
North Dakota is considering a bill that would require all
imports of farm products and livestock to be certified free of
certain chemicals. The law is scheduled to come into effect on
July 1, 2000. But the state is not blocking shipments from other
American states.
</P>
<P>
At stake is a "significant proportion of our grain shipments to
the United states," said a Canadian senior official with the
department of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Much of western Canada's grain exports to the United States are
shipped through North Dakota on two main railway lines, he said.
Grain shipments to the United States are expected to total up to
two million tons this crop year.
</P>
<P>
Cattle and hog shipments would also be threatened if the law
goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
North Dakota's technical requirements for certification would
add a huge testing burden on Canadian grain producers and subject
them to restrictions with no scientific basis, added Leslie
Swartman, spokeswoman for Canadian International Trade Minister
Sergio Marchi.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that this new law violates NAFTA, particularly
the national treatment provisions," International Trade Minister
Sergio Marchi said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. administration is responsible for ensuring that the
actions of its states conform to NAFTA. We are asking them to help
ensure that this legislation is not signed into law," added the
minister.
</P>
<P>
He officially requested consultations under NAFTA. If
consultations fall through, the dispute could go to a binding
settlement panel for resolution.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed new law would prohibit a wide range of Canadian
agricultural products from entering North Dakota without the
necessary scientific justification required by NAFTA and by
domestic U.S. regulations said Canadian Agriculture and Agri-Food
Minister Lyle Vanclief.
</P>
<P>
"There is no scientific basis for this, and we will vigorously
defend the rights of Canadian exporters of agricultural goods,"
added the minister in the same statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
