<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April  2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Britain has partially lifted a 12-year-long ban on
the entry of Israeli nuclear scientists into the country.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement, reached two months ago, Israeli nuclear
scientists who want to visit Britain for "private" purpose must
declare that they will observe the terms of the International
Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (INNPT), local daily Ha'aretz
reported Friday. Israeli nuclear scientists have been barred from
attending professional conferences or visiting research
institutions in Britain ever since Israeli agents nabbed nuclear
whistle-blower Mordechai Vanunu in Rome in 1986.(Israel-Britain-
Nuclear)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani said on Friday that
Albania will open its territory to NATO ground troops for an
eventual intervention in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French daily Liberation in Tirana,
Albania's capital, Mejdani said that NATO troops can pass and
station in Albania, which will let NATO use all of its
infrastructures like airports. "We are ready to put at the
disposal of NATO all our infrastructures like airports and other
important places for the NATO units. We are open to non-
governmental or military organizations," he said. (Albania-
Yugoslavia-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Two Iraqi civilians were injured and two houses
destroyed in southern Iraq on Friday in the first U.S.-British
airstrikes in Iraq in more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted an Iraqi military spokesman as
saying that 13 formations of F-14, F-16 and Tornado fighter jets
violated Iraqi airspace at 0900 a.m. local time. The aircraft
carried out 18 sorties from Kuwaiti skies and 33 from Saudi
airspace, supported by command and AWAKS and I-2-C planes from
Saudi Arabia, said the unidentified spokesman. (Iraq-US-Airstrikes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Gaza City -- Israel has confiscated more Palestinian land in
the southern Gaza Strip to build a new Jewish settlement in a bid
to exert fresh pressure on Palestinians seeking to declare an
independent state in May.
</P>
<P>
Israel has confiscated some 5,000 square meters of land in Khan
Younis province near the Mediterranean to build a settlement there,
the Arab daily AL-Ayyam reported Friday. Major Osam Al-Ali,
President of the joint Palestinian-Israeli Security Committee,
said that Israel had unlawfully allowed some mobile homes to be
moved into the region, which has already been enclosed by barbed
wire. (Israel-Palestinians-Land) 
