<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Purges Reported in Rwanda's Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan parliament is
reportedly undergoing serious purges with some law-makers
expelled, and others summoned to resign, the Rwanda News Agency
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The parties so far affected include the Republican Democratic
Party (MDR) , the Rwandan Patriotic Front and the Liberal Party,
the news agency quoted well-informed sources in the capital Kigali
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nothing has been disclosed about the representatives of five
other political parties forming the current transitional assembly
set up in December 1994 and comprised of 70 members.
</P>
<P>
What is so far known is that one member of parliament from the
Rwandan Patriotic Front, billionaire Valens Kajeguhakwa, resigned
on his will while three of his colleagues were asked to resign,
and did so.
</P>
<P>
Two law-makers from the Liberal Party have also resigned, but
many more could be expelled by the forum of political parties that
has taken the role of a ''censure'' organ, examining the
performance and conduct of parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
It is said that in a special convention held in Kibungo, east
of the capital Kigali, late last month, the Republican Democratic
Party executive committee sacked four of its parliamentarians the
forum of political parties had earlier asked to resign.
</P>
<P>
The four have been charged with crimes ranging from high
treason, and active collaboration with the armed Hutu insurgents,
to fostering the "Hutu Power" ideology, which is blamed for
inciting ethnic hatred among Rwandans.
</P>
<P>
They had been given fifteen days to leave on their free will or
 otherwise be sacked by their own political formations.
</P>
<P>
It is said that two other law-makers of the Republican
Democratic Party are under close examination and might be expelled
from their party because of their ''doubtful conduct'' as well.
</P>
<P>
In expelling the parliamentarians, the Democratic Party claimed
that they are hard-liners and are not supportive of the current
reforms within the party to suit for the policy of national unity
and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
But some analysts believe that this party which stands accused
of hammering in the hearts of Rwandans ethnic hate, and inciting
the Hutus to kill Tutsis since 1959, is trying to redeem its
tarnished image in vain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
