<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, British Warplanes Resume Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Two Iraqi civilians were injured
and two houses destroyed in southern Iraq Friday in the first
U.S.-British airstrikes in Iraq in more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted an Iraqi military spokesman as
saying that 13 formations of F-14, F-16 and Tornado fighter jets
violated Iraqi airspace at 0900 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft carried out 18 sorties from Kuwaiti skies and 33
from Saudi airspace, supported by command and AWAKS and I-2-C
planes from Saudi Arabia, said the unidentified spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The planes targeted civilian areas in the Afaj region of the
southern Qadissiya province, 200 kilometers south of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi air defenses encountered the enemy formations, forcing
them to flee to their bases in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia by 10:35
a.m. local time, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports say that U.S. and British warplanes committed
hostilities as well as surveillance and provocative acts from
March 1 to 15, killing and injuring hundreds of civilians and
inflicting material losses to both civilian and public properties.
</P>
<P>
Friday's report of airstrikes was the first since NATO launched
air strikes against Yugoslavia on March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
