<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke040243 -Indian Foreign Minister Likely to Visit China: Brajesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister's
Principal Secretary Brajesh Mishra said here Friday that there was
a possibility for Indian External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh
to visit China to take forward the bilateral dialogue process.
</P>
<P>
"There is also a possibility of Jaswant Singh visiting China or
holding talks with Chinese leaders at the Asian Regional Forum
meeting at Singapore in June if the talks of the Joint Working
group are fruitful," he told newsmen here.
</P>
<P>
India and China would hold the next meeting of their Joint
Working group (JWG) by the end of the month or by early May to
discuss the border problem between the two countries and other
issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last month the two countries had resumed official level
dialogue for the first time since India conducted nuclear tests in
May last year.
</P>
<P>
Jaswant Singh met Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan on the
sidelines of the annual meeting of the Asian Regional Forum last
July.
</P>
<P>
The JWG meeting was taking place in the backdrop of positive
signals emerging from both countries on bringing back on track
bilateral ties, Brajesh said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Indo-Pakistan relations, he said that the foreign
secretaries of India and Pakistan would meet in New Delhi in May
to resume talks on peace and security including
confidence-building measures and the Jammu and Kashmir issue as
part of the composite dialogue process. Official level talks on
six other issues between the two countries including Siachen,
Tulbul Navigation project would be discussed in Islamabad next
month. The whole process was expected to be completed by May, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to prospects of U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to
India, he said for this a more conducive atmosphere was needed.
With sanctions imposed against India in the aftermath of its
nuclear tests still in place, would he like to undertake the visit
under such conditions? Brajesh asked.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo crisis, he said that India was in close touch
with the non-aligned countries to forge a coordinated position on
the issue. India has severely criticized the NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia, contending that it was in clear violation of
the U.N. Charter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
