<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Stop Selling Leaded Gasoline in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Leaded gasoline will not be
available in Macao in May this year as a result of the ban on
selling leaded gas in neighboring Hong Kong beginning from April 1.
</P>
<P>
Macao mainly imports leaded gasoline from Hong Kong, and the
ban will make gas dealers in Hong Kong transport their remaining
stock to Macao. It is estimated that the stock will be sold up in
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
By that time, gas stations in Macao will supply a new kind of
fuel to vehicles which consume leaded fuel. The substitute is
produced by means of mixing a special type of additive with normal
lead-free gasoline. The mixture is said to be cheaper than leaded
gas.
</P>
<P>
On January 1, 1995, the Macao government issued a decree
requiring that newly imported or registered vehicles be equipped
with devices using lead-free fuel. However, more than 60 percent
of vehicles in Macao are still driven by leaded fuel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
