<HEADLINE> Crowds Flock to Yugoslav Films in Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- People in Shanghai and Guangzhou
are expressing their sympathy with the Yugoslav people by watching
movies which depict their struggle against the Nazis during World
War Two.
</P>
<P>
A week long Yugoslav Film festival has been launched in both
cities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the web-site of the Shanghai Cyber Club for Movie
Fans has received a lot of inquiries about Yugoslav movies,
according to a club spokesman.
</P>
<P>
To satisfy this need, the club joined forced with the Shanghai
Film Art Center, which is the slickest entertainment plaza in the
city, to organize the festival.
</P>
<P>
From today the center will show four Yugoslav movies, all of
which are very familiar to elderly people.
</P>
<P>
In Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, the
film week started yesterday and the City Cinema Company began
showing six Yugoslavia movies for only 10 yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Oriental TV has also announced that it will soon show
two Yugoslav movies about their resistance to Nazi invasion during
World War Two. The same two movies have recently been shown on
China Central Television's Movie Channel.
</P>
<P>
"Through these movies we can once again feel the unyielding
character and peace-loving nature of the Yugoslav people," a
moviegoer in Shanghai said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
