<HEADLINE> Israeli Allied Militiaman Wounded In S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A member of the pro-Israeli South
Lebanon Army (SLA) militia was wounded in south Lebanon overnight
by a roadside bomb, the Voice of the People radio reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the militia had admitted the casualty, adding
that the explosion occurred on the Biyida-Shamua road just outside
the Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
claimed responsibility for the attack, saying its fighters
detonated the roadside bomb when a SLA patrol was heading toward
its position in the central sector of the border enclave.
</P>
<P>
The blast raised to 12 the number of the militiamen wounded in
south Lebanon since the start of this year. Only one militiaman
was killed over the same period.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli occupation forces and
its allies SLA out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
