<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control over On-line Information on Rare Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China's cultural officials are to
closely check websites which provide information on its
archeological finds, rare relics and its listed World Heritage
sites following a spate of smuggling cases by gangs of
international thieves.
</P>
<P>
 A large number of antiques and relics have been secretly
excavated and removed after thieves found out the exact location
of important archeological sites from websites. They have then
been sold to dealers abroad.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Cultural Heritage (SACH) is
responsible for keeping a watch on the type of information
released and now intends to prevent classified documents and
ongoing archaeological studies from being publicized on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
SACH officials plan to purge all items from China's cultural
heritage websites that could expose important relics to security
threats.
</P>
<P>
The administration is also preparing a uniform standard for
nationwide information databases on cultural relics, which will be
introduced by all museums and relevant organizations.
</P>
<P>
China's first official cultural heritage website was set up by
the SACH earlier this year and more than 60 museums have opened
their own sites with many others planning to follow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
