<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Promotion of International Year of Older Persons in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A special event to promote the
1999 International Year of Older Persons began in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
China has the largest aging population in the world and
estimates are that there will be 120 million Chinese above the age
of 60 by the year 2000 and about 400 million by the middle of the
next century.
</P>
<P>
The event, organized by the Ministry of Health, the Chinese
Medical Association, the Chinese Association of Preventive
Medicine, is to introduce measures to deal with related problems
and also help provide the elderly with health care.
</P>
<P>
This October the first ever exposition focusing on elderly
health care facilities is to held and the Ministry of Health will
hold a seminar on health care for the aging population sometime
this year. China will also make efforts to promote the "Active
Aging" policy.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Health said that medi-care
will be the main thrust of this year's activities including an
Anti-Cancer Week, World Osteoporosis Day, National Hypertension
Day, World Diabetes Day and a National Day of Dental Health.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Health show that the health of
China's elderly population is not particularly good and that those
over 60 are three times more likely than younger people to
contract chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
And a recent survey conducted by the World Health Organization
indicates that 75 percent of the mortality rate in developing
countries including China is related to diseases amongst elderly
persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
