<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed World Cannot Impose Wishes on Others: EC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 2 (Xinhua) -- European Commission Vice
President Sir Leon Brittan said here Friday the developed world
cannot today impose its wishes on the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The future negotiations in the World Trade Organization (WTO)
will only be acceptable if the benefits are widely shared,
Brittan told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
Brittan is currently in Malaysia as part of his visit to Asian
countries which include Indonesia, India and Pakistan, for the
next round of WTO trade negotiations - the Millennium Round, which
will begin in November in Seattle, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Brittan said the interest of Malaysia and other countries in
the region could be strongly represented in the coming WTO
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"It is best, to put on the table, the interests of these
countries that need to be negotiated, unless it is felt that
everything is all right," he said
</P>
<P>
The developing world has nothing to fear if it has its own
agenda to be put on the table because "you have the obligation not
to accept what you don't want to do", Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that a comprehensive round of multilateral trade
negotiations is necessary in the current economic climate, to
stimulate growth and to reduce the risk of protectionism.
</P>
<P>
The official said that if the WTO members want the rules to be
changed then they should be ready to discuss it at the
organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
