<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Dianchi Lake Getting Clean Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A dredging project to clean the
bottom of Dianchi Lake, China's sixth largest freshwater lake near
Kunming, capital of Yunnan Province, has been completed ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
The 250-million-yuan (30 million U.S. dollars) project has
resulted in the removal of 4.2 million cubic meters of silt on a 2.
8-square-kilometer area. With the completion of the project, the
water quality of the lake will be greatly improved, according to a
State Environmental Protection Administration official.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the pollutants cleaned from the bottom of the
lake include 7,990 tons of phosphorus, 39,600 tons of nitrogen,
and more than 5,000 tons of heavy metals. The water storage
capacity of the lake has also been increased by 4.2 million cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
The lake is on a high plateau and plays a key role in the
ecology of Kunming, but it has been seriously polluted by
industrial and urban waste.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Chinese government listed Dianchi as one of the
key parts of the "three rivers and three lakes" project that
covers the Liaohe, Huaihe, and Haihe rivers and Taihu, Chaohu, and
Dianchi lakes.
</P>
<P>
This year, the government has sped up the cleaning work on
Dianchi to finish it in time for the World Horticulture Exposition,
which starts early in May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
