<HEADLINE> ICRC Appalled by Killings of Four Sudanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A Red Cross Sudanese worker and
three government officials accompanying a team of the
International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) in southern Sudan were
killed by the Sudanese rebels, said an ICRC release available here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
It said four Sudanese accompanied an ICRC team on a mission
near the southern Sudanese town of Bentiu on February 18 and
inadvertently strayed into the territory held by the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA) . Two ICRC expatriates and the
four Sudanese were captured.
</P>
<P>
The release said the two expatriates were released on March 12,
but the four Sudanese were still detained by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
After more than one month and despite its immediate and
sustained efforts, the ICRC was unable to secure the release of
the four men.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that during the visit to Geneva by John
Garang, chairman of the Sudanese rebel movement, on March 22, ICRC
President Cornelio Sommaruga privately urged Garang to set free
the detained persons without delay.
</P>
<P>
"The ICRC is shocked and appalled at the news of the death of
the four Sudanese, in particular that of a Red Crescent worker,
and the SPLA cannot but be held accountable for their death," said
the release.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC demanded a full inquiry to shed light on the events
and the full cooperation of the rebel movement in repatriating
the bodies to allow for a decent burial, the release concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
