<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Set for Explosive Growth in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua)-- The Internet is witnessing
explosive growth in China, with highly-educated young people
accounting for the bulk of the surfers, according to the result of
a recent survey released today.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair, a Beijing-based consultation company, launched a
nationwide survey to find out the readiness of Chinese people to
take up the latest information technology.
</P>
<P>
The survey, under guidance of the Ministry of Information
Industry, found that 71.2 percent of non-Internet-surfers are very
interested in getting acquainted with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
It also discovered that 85.6 percent of surfers are seeking
information on science, technology, and political and social
matters, while 70.8 percent of those questioned log on to the net
to send and receive e-mails.
</P>
<P>
The major means of learning about the Internet is through
actual surfing on the net and 52.9 percent of surfers claim the
magazine "Computer World" is the most helpful and influential
media source for their familiarity with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that the majority of those questioned, whether
they are surfers or not, have acquired basic knowledge and know-
how about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
However, the surfers said that the real age of e-commerce will
arrive in about two to three years.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that 66.3 percent of surfers have computers at
home and that an average surfer stays on the net for five hours
and 16 minutes a week.
</P>
<P>
However, the surfers complained about the slow speed of logging
on to the net. In addition, 71.6 percent of the non-net-surfers
cite the arbitrary cost as the major obstacle that prevents them
from logging on.
</P>
<P>
The survey was carried out in September-December last year but
recently China has substantially dropped its Internet charges.
</P>
<P>
The Sinclair company received 10,408 effective replies to their
questionnaires, which were handed out nationwide through the
Internet and traditional newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
More than 85 percent of those surveyed are aged below 35 years
of age, and over 77 percent of them have received a college
education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
