<HEADLINE> Kenya's Moi Names Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
Friday re- appointed George Saitoti as the country's Vice
President, putting an end to speculations and protest from both
the opposition and the Kenyan public as a whole over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Before the appointment, Saitoti had served as Minister of
Planning and National Development since 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old professor was Vice-President and Finance
Minister in Moi's last presidential term between 1992 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
On his arrival from a four-day tour to Namibia and Malawi
Thursday, Moi announced that he would name a vice-president soon
to fill the number-two post, which remained vacant since last
January.
</P>
<P>
The long-time vacancy of the post had aroused concern from the
Kenyan public. Kenya's major newspapers recently had carried front
page stories entitled "Give Us a VP" , "17 MPs Say No to An Extra
Moi Term" and the like.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's opposition parties have indicted Moi for failing to
appoint a vice-president as stipulated by the current
constitution.
</P>
<P>
A legislator from the opposition Ford-Kenya has submitted a
motion of censure of Moi to Kenyan National Assembly (parliament)
ahead of its April 6 reopening after the adjournment since last
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parities alleged that Moi's non-compliance with
the constitution affected negatively on the constitutional review
process.
</P>
<P>
They also argued there was no constitutional basis for Moi to
stay in office beyond the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
They opposed any attempt to change the current constitution to
allow Moi to serve an extra term.
</P>
<P>
Political observers believe Moi's appointment of a
vice-president is meant to appease the debate. 
</P>
