<HEADLINE> Tanzania Calls for Lifting of Embargo on Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has said the
economic embargo on Cuba should be lifted so that economy of the
Caribbean country could pick up.
</P>
<P>
Shamim Khan, deputy minister for industry and commerce, said
Thursday Tanzania's relationship with Cuba has been healthy for a
long time but the troubled economy of both countries has hampered
the carrying out of crucial agreements on various development
issues.
</P>
<P>
Khan made the remarks at a signing ceremony for bilateral
cooperation in education and health sectors in Dar es Salaam
Thursday, the independent newspaper Daily Mail reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was also attended by Cuba's Deputy Minister for
Foreign Investment and Economic Cooperation, Noemi Benitez.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed an agreement to meet every six months
instead of two years as was the case before.
</P>
<P>
Khan expressed hopes that international sanctions imposed on
the island economy decades ago could be over soon.
</P>
<P>
She said with the lifting of international embargo on Cuba and
Tanzania' s success in economic reform, programs of cooperation in
various areas of development would be implemented.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Cuban deputy minister said her country is quite
comfortable with Tanzania's foreign policy on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Cuban's economy has been receding since the fall of the Eastern
Bloc in the early 90s, she said, adding that currently new
economic programs have been drafted to meet global economic
demands.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the two countries met last time in 1997 in
Havana, Cuba. The Cuban deputy minister also invited Khan,
Minister of Science, Technology and Higher Education and the
Minister of Health to visit her country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
