<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Firms Getting Help by Stock Listing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- For the debt-ridden state sector
in China's Liaoning Province, which was once a key industrial base,
getting listed on the stock exchange has proved to be a good way
to get out of their financial mess.
</P>
<P>
The listed companies have provided a good example for poorly-
run state-owned enterprises (SOEs) in the province, as only one of
the 49 listed companies is expecting losses for 1998, while 45
percent of the large and medium-sized SOEs are losing money in
Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
These companies have become a force for restoring Liaoning to
its former glory, said Su Yong, chairman of the Provincial
Securities Regulatory Commission. Liaoning had a tenth of China's
large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Of the province's 49 listed companies, 46 are considered large
or medium-sized.
</P>
<P>
There are good reasons for the good results with the listed
companies. To get listed, an enterprise has to restructure itself
first, get rid of debt and non-performing assets and establish a
modern enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has selected companies in industries with good
prospects for public listing. Almost half are in the machinery,
metallurgical, electronic, and petrochemical sectors, the four
pillars of Liaoning's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Firms Getting Help by Stock Listing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The state sector needs more funds for technical renovation and
product mix adjustment, and funds from the securities market are
like "charcoal in snowy weather", Su said.
</P>
<P>
The better performance has also attracted banks and most of the
listed companies have agent banks and get privileged treatment in
loans and other banking services.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, commercial banks and local governments in Liaoning put
several billion yuan into the listed companies for key technical
renovations and infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Observers here say that the public listing also puts the
companies under the closer scrutiny of investors and securities
regulators and encourages the companies to adjust to the market
economy.
</P>
<P>
"We have to answer to the shareholders after listing on the
securities market and we may lose our jobs if the company can not
report favorable results. This pressures me to rack my brains to
run the company," said Lin Yi, vice-president of Liaoning's Jindi
Group.
</P>
<P>
Public listing also led to acquisitions and mergers. Liaotong
Petrochemicals, for example, became China's top fertilizer
producer by acquiring 95.7 percent of the stock of a provincial
natural gas producer, which had been mired in more than two
billion yuan in debt but got out of its financial difficulties
after the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
Liu Ketian, vice-governor of Liaoning, said that the province
will continue to list state-owned companies and promote assets
relocation of listed companies in order to revitalize the state
sector.
</P>
<P>
"We are also pushing for large securities companies in Liaoning
with the aim of reinvigorating the industrial base," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Suspends Ban on Israeli Nuclear Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain has partially lifted a
12-year-long ban on the entry of Israeli nuclear scientists into
the country.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement, reached two months ago, Israeli nuclear
scientists who want to visit Britain for "private" purpose must
declare that they will observe the terms of the International
Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (INNPT), local daily Ha'aretz
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli nuclear scientists have been barred from attending
professional conferences or visiting research institutions in
Britain ever since Israeli agents nabbed nuclear whistle-blower
Mordechai Vanunu in Rome in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The ban was applied to nuclear scientists and those working in
associated fields, such as the development of biological and
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from Israel's research institutions, such as the
Weizman Institute, the Nuclear Research Centers at Dimona, Nahal
Sorek and Raphael and the Israel Armament Development Authority
were under the ban.
</P>
<P>
Britain imposed the ban under its commitment to the INNPT,
which Israel has not signed, the daily quoted Simon Pease, the
deputy head of mission of the British Embassy in Tel Aviv as
saying.
</P>
<P>
And the 1986 Vanunu episode made it clear that Israel was a
nuclear state.
</P>
<P>
Britain adopted the tough attitude towards Israeli scientists
after Vanunu gave an interview to the London Sunday Times in
October 1986, in which Vanunu divulged the existence of Israel's
nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
Soon after, Israeli agents enticed Vanunu to leave Britain and
travel to Italy, where he was abducted, brought forcibly back
to Israel and sentenced to 18 years in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
