<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Friday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic won two points in a
psychological war with NATO on Thursday, by presenting the picture
of three captured American soldiers on television and receiving
Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova before cameras in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
-- In the United States, the images of the three American
soldiers captured by Serb forces have increased pressure on
Washington for sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Liberation, Albanian President Rexhep
Mejdani said that his country is ready to receive NATO ground
troops for an eventual intervention in Kosovo. Albania, the
poorest country in Europe, is submerged by a huge influx of Kosovo
refugees, who continued to flow in on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- NATO put up an intact determination on Thursday in its war
with Yugoslavia, despite the capture of three GI's by Serb forces.
The U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said that NATO does not
have the intention to change direction, while U.S. President Bill
Clinton held Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic "personally
responsible" for the safety of the three American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
-- The moderate Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova met with
Milosevic on Thursday in Belgrade and the two men promised to seek
an end to the conflict in Kosovo through "political means."
Meanwhile, Pope John Paul II has appealed for a truce during the
Easter.
</P>
<P>
Le Monde:
</P>
<P>
-- More than 130,000 Kosovo Albanians have fled their homes
within one week, said the High Commissioner of the United Nations
for Refugees. The situation of the refugees in Albania, Macedonia
and Montenegro is becoming precarious and causing great concern.
</P>
<P>
-- While doubts are increasing about the effectiveness of
airstrikes on Yugoslavia, NATO is intensifying its bombings there.
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said on Thursday that the
bombings would go on for weeks rather than days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
