<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Files Antique Buildings in Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has started to make
an inventory of all the old buildings throughout the country and
store the information in a computer network.
</P>
<P>
Donatus Kamamba, director of the Department of Antiquities,
said here Thursday that the exercise will help collect and
computerize all the information on old buildings currently in
paper files and scattered.
</P>
<P>
He said experts are visiting all the old buildings in the
country and recording their conditions, the Daily Mail newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Once the task that started in January this year is completed,
Kamamba said, the information synthesized will facilitate the
identification of old buildings located in various parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
"We should be able to get information on any old buildings in
the country, like its owner, age and current condition and make
them easily available,"he said.
</P>
<P>
Kamamba said the job will take long and is likely to be
finished next year because the department lacks computers and
financial support needed to speed up the exercise.
</P>
<P>
"If we had the computers and the financial support, this job
would have taken as short as three months to complete," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Antiquities is empowered by Tanzania's
Antiquities Act of 1964 to take care of all the old buildings in
the country which are deemed to have historical, archaeological or
any other extraordinary importance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
