<HEADLINE> North China Urban Air Quality Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The air quality of many cities in
north China was better this week compared with the previous week,
according to the latest report released by the China Environmental
Monitoring Center today.
</P>
<P>
With the coming of spring, many northern cities have stopped
burning coal for heating and decreased the release of pollutants
into the air.
</P>
<P>
However, Beijing endured heavy fog during the week and because
of slow wind speeds had an unfavorable environment for dispersing
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou, Guilin, Beihai, Zhanjiang, Haikou, Ningbo, Shenzhen and
Xiamen enjoyed excellent air quality from March 26 to April 1,
while 21 cities including Chongqing, Guangzhou, Shanghai, Dalian
and Nanjing reported good air quality.
</P>
<P>
Twelve cities including Tianjin, Changchun, Xining, Shenyang,
Kunming and Xi'an reported slight air pollution during the period.
Beijing, Taiyuan and Yinchuan reported medium air pollution, and
Lanzhou and Hohhot suffered from serious pollution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
