<HEADLINE> Israeli Humanitarian Aid Flown to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua)-- An Israeli plane loaded with
medical and humanitarian aid for Kosovo refugees left Ben Gurion
International Airport Friday morning for Albania.
</P>
<P>
This ten-tonne aid shipment, including medicines, blankets and
tents, was finally taken off after being delayed Wednesday due to
problems with overfly permission from the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), which is still carrying out airstrikes
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon told the Israeli delegation at
the airport that the Israeli government is worried about the
situation in Kosovo and the Kosovo crisis could only be solved
through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The delegation was headed by Science Minister Silvan Shalon
and Air Force Commander Maj. Gen. Eitan Ben-Eliyahu. The Plane
is expected back in Israel Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The decision to sent out the airlift was taken at the special
cabinet meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government officials have different opinions towards the
Kosovo issue. Sharon has repeatedly said that Kosovo crisis
could end through peaceful means, urging the parties concerned
to return to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
But Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Thursday night that
he supports the NATO's military action against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry officials and several other Israeli historians
have expressed their reservations of taking stands against the
Serbs in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav people had saved many lives of the Jews during the
World War II, and Israel should never forget this, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
