<HEADLINE> Japan Offers Medical Help to Flood-Stricken Areas in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Japan is to donate 897 million yen
worth of immunization equipment to seven Chinese provinces that
were severely hit by floods last year and lost a lot of their own
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The equipment will be used to ensure the health of children in
the flood-stricken areas along the Yangtze River valley and the
Songhua River valley.
</P>
<P>
These are the highlights of the "Expanded Program on
Immunization Plan" signed here today by Long Yongtu, chief
negotiator of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, and Sakutaro Tanino, Japanese ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
The devastating floods last year caused great damage to medical
supplies and immunization equipment.
</P>
<P>
Today's announcement is only a third of the aid program
promised by Japan since March 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the announcement, the "Dike Improvement Project on the
Yangtze River" stipulates that Japan will provide 1.46 billion yen
worth of steel piling and construction equipment, which will be
used to reinforce dikes along the Yangtze River and to prevent
seepage.
</P>
<P>
To carry out the "Grain Production Increase Aid Project",
involving a 1.32 billion yen government aid, Japan will assist six
provinces including Yunnan, Guizhou and Shaanxi, to buy farming
machinery, fertilizers, chemicals and vehicles to help local
farmers improve agricultural development and food production.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been involved in China's immunization work by
providing vaccines and laboratory equipment valued at more than
900 million yen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
