<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Charges Ex Rwandan Mayor with Genocide Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) charged Thursday a former Rwandan mayor
with 13 counts of genocide crimes, an ICTR press release said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, Ignace Bagilishema, a former Bourgmestre (mayor) of
Mabanza Commune in Kibuye Prefecture of Rwanda pleaded !0not
guilty!1 to the charges.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR Trial Chamber 2 charged Bagilishema, 45, with
Conspiracy to Commit Genocide, Genocide, Crimes against Humanity,
and Violation of Article 3 Common to the Geneva Convention and of
Additional Protocol II.
</P>
<P>
The plea was entered on his behalf by judges William Sekule
(presiding), Tafazzal Khan and Yakov Ostrovsky after the accused
failed to enter a plea of !0guilty!1 or !0not guilty!1 during his
initial appearance.
</P>
<P>
Bagilishema, born in 1954 in Mabanza, is alleged to have
murdered, assisted and conspired to murder thousands of Tutsis
throughout Kibuye Prefecture between April 9 and June 30 1994.
</P>
<P>
On or about April 17, 1994, the release said, Bagilishema was
alleged to have ordered men, women and children into the Catholic
Church and Home St. Jean Complex, and into the Stadium in Kibuye.
!0Massacres did indeed take place and thousands of people inside
the complex and the stadium were killed or injured with the
attackers using guns, grenades, machetes, spears, cudgels and
other weapons,!1 it read.
</P>
<P>
Bagilishema turned up in South Africa on February 16 1999 and
signed a declaration agreeing to surrender himself to the
Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
On February 20, the Tribunal served him with a warrant of
arrest in Pretoria, where he had been detained by South African
authorities in connection with his immigration status and he was
transferred to the Tribunal Detention Facilities in Arusha the
same day.
</P>
<P>
Established on November 8 1994 by the United Nations Security
Council, the ICTR has the mandate to try persons suspected to be
responsible for genocide and other serious violations of the
international humanitarian law committed in the territory of
Rwanda between January 1 and December 31, 1994.
</P>
<P>
It also has the mandate to try Rwandan citizens responsible for
such violations committed in the territory of neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR has so far issued 28 indictments against 45
individuals and a total of 36 indicted individuals are in custody,
35 of them in the United Nations Detention Facilities in Arusha
and one is detained in Texas of the United States.
</P>
<P>
About half a million Rwandan Tutis and moderate Hutus were
reportedly killed during the 1994 genocide when the majority Hutus
oppressed the minority Tutis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
