<HEADLINE> Congolese Refugees to Return from Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Several hundreds of refugees from
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) are on their way to their
home country from Kaputa in Zambia's the Northern Province.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, mostly soldiers in military attire, were being
ferried in seven buses Thursday and escorted by heavily armed
Zambian soldiers and officers from the Office of the President
Special Division, Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kaputa Council Chief Administrator John Mwilye confirmed that
the Zambian government had hired buses to ferry over 500 Congolese
who requested to go back home.
</P>
<P>
Kampata Banda, public relations official of the Red Cross
Society of Zambia, said in Lusaka Thursday there were about 15,647
registered persons at the reception camp in Kaputa while many
others are living in surrounding villages of the district.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commissioner of Refugees (UNHCR)
announced last week that the situation in Kaputa was worrying and
that medical facilities and accommodation were becoming scarce due
to the increased number of refugees.
</P>
<P>
UNHRC public relations official Diminik Barstch said apart from
Kaputa Rural Health Clinic, another center has been established to
cater for the refugees at the reception camp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
