<HEADLINE> Sihanoukville's Toxic Waste Shipped back to Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Sihanoukville's illegally
dumped mercury-laden waste was forced Friday to temporarily ship
back to its original producing place, Taiwan, as the U.S. withdrew
permission for it to be shipped to California.
</P>
<P>
Three thousand tons toxic waste, illegally dumped on a hill 15
km from Sihanoukville town in early last December, was shipped
from the Taiwanese company Formosa Plastics Corp. and caused a
panic in the seaside town after it was discovered.
</P>
<P>
Illnesses and at least two deaths have been reported, but no
direct link to the waste has been established.
</P>
<P>
The ship carrying the waste left Sihanoukville Port Friday
morning to Taiwan. Three thousand tons of toxic waste plus 2000
tons of top-soil taken from the toxic waste hilltop were
repackaged into 18,000 oil barrels which were stored in more than
350 containers.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, government officials presided over a ceremony
closing the dump site and declaring the area safe.
</P>
<P>
As the containers were being loaded, however, the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) withdrew its earlier
approval fro the waste to be stored in the state of California.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the EPA had independent test results that
show higher levels mercury than the studies submitted in
Safty-Kleen's storage application. Safty-kleen is a U.S.-based
company who contracted to dispose of the waste in California.
</P>
<P>
The waste was also protested by California communities and
environmental activists in the U.S.. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
