<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Must Reform Investment, Financing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China's current investment and
financing system continues to feature characteristics of a planned
economy and may result in high financial risks if allowed to
remain unchanged, according to a senior official in charge of the
monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
State-owned and loss-making enterprises continue to enjoy
advantages in terms of access to funding.
</P>
<P>
Increased Government allocations would simply increase the flow
of funding to state-owned enterprises and result in an even
greater waste of resources, according to Yi Gang, deputy secretary-
general of the State Council's Monetary Policy Commission.
</P>
<P>
Yi proposed radical reform of the system in line with laws
governing of a market economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the government should narrow its area of investment for
state-owned enterprises and focus on expanding the investment area
and channels available to the non-public sector. He added that
businesses in the latter sector should be allowed to invest in
areas dominated by the government, including infrastructure and
public projects.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses should be allowed to enter sectors
monopolized by state-owned enterprises in order to create rational
competition. This in turn would lead to the demise of loss-making
state-owned enterprises and ensure sustainable national economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Yi, who also serves as deputy director of the Monetary Policy
Department of the People's Bank of China, called for creating a
financing environment in which all enterprises are equally treated
regardless of ownership type.
</P>
<P>
Government intervention in capital market must be halted and
stock market listings for enterprise must be decided by the market
rather than the government, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He also cited the need for improving the financing service
system to meet the needs of small- to medium-sized enterprises.
This in turn would facilitate the establishment of floating
interest rates on loans to related enterprises, as well as the
establishment of insurance funds for additional loans, according
to Yi.
</P>
<P>
He said the process to commercialize state-owned banks should
be accelerated in order to ensure banks improve management and
services and grant profit-oriented loans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Freezing Aid To Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has denied that
it had frozen aid to Zimbabwe on the basis of bad human rights
record and alleged disregard of the rule of law, the daily Herald
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here in the Zimbabwean capital
Thursday, the U.S. Embassy said instead, the United States Agency
for International Development (USAID) director was currently in
Washington, calling for the extension of U.S. assistance to
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact, USAID Director Rose Marie Depp is
currently in Washington presenting a comprehensive program
strategy to U.S. government officials that clearly calls for an
extension, not suspension, of U.S. assistance to Zimbabwe," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, any such decision would have been conveyed by the
embassy promptly to the Zimbabwean government through customary
diplomatic channels; in this case it was not, because U.S.
government aid has not been suspended and the newspaper account
that suggests such is unequivocally false," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Quoting an unnamed government official from Washington, The
Financial Gazette, Zimbabwe's weekly paper, alleged that the U.S.
had frozen all outstanding aid to Zimbabwe worth about 120 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
