<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Unearth Ancient Carriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists recently
unearthed a 3,000-year-old tomb holding the remains of one man,
two horses and a carriage.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists surmise that the tomb unearthed in central
China's Henan Province was a chariot pit. They also point to
possibility of additional large tomb in the area to hold the
remains of either a member of the royal family or a high level
official.
</P>
<P>
The tomb was unearthed at Yinxu, the famous ruins of the
capital of the Shang Dynasty (16th-11th century B.C.). Ancient
Chinese living during the Shang Dynasty developed the earliest
characters inscribed on bones and tortoise shells.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is in a high state of preservation, according to the
archeologists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
