<HEADLINE> Noted Chinese Writer Calls for Teaching Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Noted Chinese writer Wang Meng
recently called teaching reform in China's primary and middle
schools, according to Wednesday's edition of Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Teaching students to use their brains to write in their own
language is extremely important", according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
The former Minister of Culture stressed the need to replace
standardized test forms.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that multiple choice tests are suited to the
English language which is clearly classified by different parts of
speeches. However, he stressed that multiple choice tests fail to
accurately reflect the language level of Chinese students.
</P>
<P>
"The difference in the Chinese language is subtle and we
understand the meaning of a Chinese word through context", said
Wang.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that teachers should encourage students use their
own words to express what they see, feel and desire.
</P>
<P>
Wang, born in 1934, authored the novel "Long Live Youth",
novellas such as "Butterflies" and "Bolshevik Salute", and short
stories such as the "Sound of Spring". 
</P>
</TEXT>
