<HEADLINE> Foreign Fruits Flooding N. W. Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- South African fruits have flooded
markets in Kenya's northwestern Rift Valley Province, as a result
of local transport problems which restricted local fruits to
reach local markets.
</P>
<P>
"We received our supplies from the interior parts of Rift
Valley province in the past, but the supply has been dropping
alarmingly since the start of the rains" in March, said local
peddler Ruth Njeri, according to Friday's East African Standard
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Many traders said the heavy rain had made roads between the
fruit- growing area and the markets in the province impassable.
</P>
<P>
The hawkers at the local markets said orange shortage was the
most biting, compelling them to travel to capital Nairobi for
imported oranges from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Consumers complained over the high prices of fruits, especially
oranges, saying the price of a 25-kilogram bag of oranges was 800
shillings (about 12.5 U.S. dollars), a sharp rise from the past.
</P>
<P>
However, traders said they have to include the costs of
transporting products from Nairobi, adding that they purchased at
a higher wholesale price compared to what they paid to their
traditional suppliers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
