<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Strengthens Yangtze River Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province, an
economic powerhouse in the country, has set a deadline for local
enterprises to cease discharging pollutants into the Yangtze River,
the longest in China.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of a national effort to control pollution
along the Yangtze and other major rivers.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu enterprises will be required to meet provincial
wastewater discharge standards in order to avoid closure.
</P>
<P>
Mayors from Nanjing, Yangzhou, Suzhou, Zhenjiang, Taizhou,
Nantong and Wuxi cities have signed responsibility contracts
promising to meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing Mayor Wang Hongmin said his city, a major industrial
center and the provincial capital, will halt all related
wastewater discharges by July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The city has allocated 197 million yuan for pollution control
projects involving 106 enterprises, which currently discharge 800
million tons of wastewater into the Yangtze annually.  
</P>
