<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh May Expect Drought This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- With little rain over the past
several months, meteorologists here are wondering whether
Bangladesh is heading for a 10-year-cycle drought this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the Space Resource and Remote Sensing Organization
prefer to wait till the end of the first week of April before
drawing any conclusion. But fears of a drought is deepening,
considering the current sequence -- long spell of drought in 1979
and 1989 in an interval of 10 years, according to a report in The
Daily Star on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Quite anxiously we're observing the current dry spell and not
certain yet whether this is going to be another drought after
those in 1979 and 1989," the report quoted a source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The long spell of drought in 1979 continued till May and in
1989 it came to an end in April with a devastating tornado.
Experts fear that if the current spell of dry weather ends with
hailstorms and tornadoes, it will certainly take a heavy toll on
standing crops.
</P>
<P>
There is another strong sign of a possible drought, the report
said. Usually a flood of big magnitude precedes the 10-year-cycle
drought, as the country experienced severe floods in 1978 and
1988, and Bangladesh was hit by a worst flood last year.
</P>
<P>
But experts think it is rather premature to jump to a
conclusion. "It would be a bit premature to call the dry spell a
'cycle-drought' at this stage... We prefer to call it a
'non-rainfall' situation," a weather expert said.
</P>
<P>
Over the period between November 25 last year and March 15 this
year, only one-millimeter rainfall was recorded at Mongla Port,
Southwest Bangladesh, on February 6, and some traces of rain in
northwestern Rangpur and Dianjpur districts.
</P>
<P>
Slight to moderate rainfall was recorded in different parts of
the country since mid-March, but that "should not be misunderstood
as an end to the dry spell," according to one meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
The level of water of the country's major rivers such as Padma,
Jamuna, Brahmaputra, Gorai and Teesta has fallen sharply and
people are suffering from want of drinking water, reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
