<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Paper Use Soars Despite Internet Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to predictions and
forecasts, paper use in the United States continues to swell even
as more people go online and use e-mail.
</P>
<P>
Between 1990 and 1998, annual paper consumption in the country
rose from 86.8 million tons to 99 million tons, said PaperCom., a
non-profit group that studies the future of paper-based products
and services.
</P>
<P>
"Paper is emerging as the currency of the electronic era," said
the group in a report this week. "People may read online, but if
something is important they save it on paper."
</P>
<P>
Morning newspaper sales, the use of paper checks and postal
volume have all increased as Internet usage has expanded, the
group said.
</P>
<P>
"While the Internet and paper products will surely compete in
some areas," said the group in the report, "the general pattern is
one of mutual growth and interdependence."
</P>
<P>
Morning newspaper circulation in the United States went up from
40.4 million copies in 1988 to an estimated 45.4 million in 1997,
according to PaperCom.
</P>
<P>
Mail volume rose from 166.4 billion pieces in 1992 to almost
200 billion last year, while envelope sales were at an all-time
high in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, advertising mail volume reached a record high of 82.
87 billion pieces in 1998 against 62.54 billion in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The volume of paper checks rose from 57.5 billion in 1991 to 66
billion in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Face Shortage of Arable Land: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh would soon have to face a
severe shortage of arable land which is being depleted by
increasing human settlement every year.
</P>
<P>
The total cultivable land of the country now stands
approximately at 9 million hectares, which is shrinking every year
and human settlement specially for housing has been identified as
the main reason, according to a recent study by the U.N.
Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Depicting a frustrating picture of the contraction of arable
land in this South Asian nation, the study said that by the year
2025, the growing population pressure would use up 50 percent of
the country's cultivable land for settlement.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 13 persons share one hectare of land at present
and with the population reaching 170 million by the year 2020, one
hectare of land would be shared by 20 people, according to the
study, which was submitted to the Ministry of Land last week.
</P>
<P>
Unplanned rural settlement on the arable land has been causing
adverse effects on the country's total agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The industrial development and acquisition of land by the
government for different purposes have also been causing a
negative impact on the condition of the farmers and on the
socioeconomic scenario of the country.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, land is being fragmented in the countryside every
year due to the growing population and the law of inheritance,
creating a negative impact on the efficient use of land and its
productivity.
</P>
<P>
The estimated population of Bangladesh was 110 million in 1991
and it reached 126 million in January 1998. Rapid population
growth and little or no change in the land area reduced the
land-man ratio drastically from 0.8 hectares in 1951 to 0.32
hectares in 1991 and to 0.28 hectares in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The dwindling per capita land resource is expected to diminish
further as the population increases and agricultural land is
converted into other purposes.
</P>
<P>
Of the country's 14.74 million hectares of prime agricultural
land, 63 percent is used for cultivation, 4.38 for rural and urban
housing, and the rest is forest and cultivable waste land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
