<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Official Faces Tricky Race for WTO Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The race for the World Trade
Organization (WTO) top post has become tricky for Thailand's
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panichpakdi after Washington'
secret veto against him.
</P>
<P>
Thai government officials said however that they still pinned
hope on Supachai to win the job.
</P>
<P>
The WTO failed to agree on the appointment of a new
director-general at a meeting in Geneva earlier this week after
the United States reportedly rejected the Thai candidate, causing
a deadlock in the race.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will reconvene next week after the Easter break.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said on Thursday that
he believed Supachai, also commerce minister, was still in the
race against U.S.-backed rival Michael Moore from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"Other people might have felt disheartened by what has
happened. But I still have hope that he will get the job," Chuan
said.
</P>
<P>
The selection of a new WTO director-general has become a
two-man race between Supachai and Moore, former New Zealand prime
minister, after Moroccan candidate Hassan Abouyoub and Canadian
candidate Roy Maclaren pulled out of the race.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has been lobbying hard for Supachai to be
appointed the new WTO director-general and had made it an issue of
national prestige. But reports from Geneva indicate that both
Supachai and his rival face stiff resistance from some key WTO
member nations.
</P>
<P>
The contest to succeed outgoing WTO chief Renato Ruggiero of
Italy has dragged on for six months, missing several deadlines.
His term expires at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
Decisions in the WTO are taken by consensus rather than voting
among the 134 member countries. This method, its supporters claim,
helps avoid bitterness and maintains cohesion.
</P>
<P>
But trade analysts and envoys said that unless the leadership
impasse was resolved soon it could split the group and have a
serious effect on preparations for the planned launch of a new
round of global trade liberalization negotiations before the
year's end.
</P>
<P>
There was speculation that the deadlock could open the way for
a compromise decision that would allow Maclaren, Canada's former
trade minister, to rejoin the race and win the post.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the WTO and its predecessor the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade have always been headed by a European and
developing countries have been increasingly vocal in calling for
the appointment of a figure from their midst.
</P>
<P>
Supachai has promised to bridge the gap between developing
economies and richer nations if he wins the position. He has
earned international respect for his role in ensuring that
Thailand resisted pressure to put up trade barriers in reaction to
the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Supachai has already won backing from the Asia-Pacific region,
but it seems that he needs European Union (EU) support against a
strong U.S. campaign against him.
</P>
<P>
The EU is split. Sweden has taken a strong stance against
Supachai, while most nations back or do not oppose him. Other EU
members were launching a last-ditch effort to form a united
support by convincing the Swedes to switch its backing from Moore
to Supachai before the next attempt at consensus on April 14.
</P>
<P>
Moore, who has held a range of government posts in New Zealand,
is championed by the United States and also has a good mix of
support from North and South.
</P>
<P>
After the inconclusive meeting on Wednesday, the latest of
several failed deadlines in six months of efforts to appoint a new
WTO chief, U.S. Ambassador in Geneva Rita Hayes voiced confidence
that Moore would eventually win.
</P>
<P>
Some delegates charged that she was telling many countries, in
confidence, that Washington would never allow Supachai to become
the new WTO chief and that they had better vote against him.
</P>
<P>
Leon Brittan, the EU trade commissioner, accused the United
States of using a secret veto against Supachai.
</P>
<P>
"Any vetoes against particular candidates, whoever they are,
should in my view be disclosed to other members," he said.
"Anonymous votes" were inconsistent with efforts to ensure
transparency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
