<HEADLINE> China Science Museum Adds New Exhibits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing-based China Science
and Technology Museum, the sole national science museum in the
country, opened a fractal art area to the public here today.
</P>
<P>
The 240-square-meter show area was co-funded by AT&AMP;T of the
United States, which provided 75,000 US dollars from the AT&AMP;T NEAT
foundation for the establishment of the show area.
</P>
<P>
The fractal art show includes 17 items of exhibits, which
physically demonstrate the frontier science of using mathematical
models to depict the insight of the nature.
</P>
<P>
The Museum won AT&AMP;T funding through an international bidding
process for the unique and innovative plan of its fractal art
program.
</P>
<P>
The AT&AMP;T NEAT foundation offers biennial grants to science
museums around the world to encourage them to initiate new
programs that combines science with art.
</P>
<P>
China Science and Technology Museum, located in northern suburb
of Beijing, receives more than 700,000 visitors every year. It
will be able to receive one million visitors per year after
completion of the second phase of construction this year.
</P>
