<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will get a further
200,000 job opportunities abroad following the visit of Labor
Minister John Seneviratne to several Middle East countries
recently, the official Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Minister Seneviratne was quoted as saying he had led a
top-level delegation to several Gulf countries including Saudi
Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Jordan and Lebanon,
where he had favorable discussions with local industrialists.
</P>
<P>
The job market in those countries for Sri Lankans was very
satisfactory and there were a large number of skilled and
unskilled jobs available, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The lack of manpower resulted in Sri Lankan workers getting
more employment opportunities in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that private job agencies had also played a key role
in helping obtain employment for Sri Lankans in those countries.
</P>
<P>
There are around 1 million Sri Lankans employed in the Middle
East and Far East countries. Migrant workers' remittance has been
one of the main sources of foreign exchange in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan migrant workers remitted 60 billion rupees (880
million U.S. dollars) in 1998, a 9-percent increase in rupee terms
over the previous year. 
