<HEADLINE> NATO Apologizes for Deaths of Yugoslav Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- NATO has apologized for the
deaths of nine refugees earlier this week at two refugee centers
in Yugoslavia, CARE Australia, an Australian non-governmental aid
agency, said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two centers were part of a refugee network run by CARE
Australia on behalf of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
Care Australia quoted Friday the British newspaper The
Independent as reporting that Supreme Headquarters Allied Power
Europe, NATO's European headquarters, had expressed regret for the
accidental damage to two CARE refugee centers in the Yugoslav city
of Nis.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kaemmerer, spokesman for the headquarters, said, "We
are very sorry for the loss of civilian lives in this instance and
we very much regret the loss of life."
</P>
<P>
CARE Australia Chief Executive Charles Tapp said he was pleased
that NATO has accepted responsibility for the incidents and hoped
that the admission meant that the location of refugee centers
would be taken into account in future.
</P>
<P>
"Care (Australia) has requested that the U.N. agency
responsible for refugees, UNHCR, provide those responsible for the
incident with information that will help avoid a repeat of this
tragedy," Tapp said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The refugees living at the CARE Australia centers were ethnic
Serbs, mainly women and children, who had been driven from their
homes during the earlier Balkans conflict, the agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
