<HEADLINE> Solana: NATO to Continue Air Strikes on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, April 1 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana said on Thursday that NATO will continue air strikes on
Yugoslavia until President Slobodan Milosevic accepts the peace
plan proposed in last months talks in France to solve the Kosovo
issue.
</P>
<P>
Solana, in an interview with a Spanish television, said that
NATO military strike against Yugoslavia was a task of weeks
instead of a few days.
</P>
<P>
Defending the ongoing military action, Solana said that the
political aim of NATO air strikes is to give autonomy to ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, to secure the borders and promote democracy
in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
NATO's actions did not amount to war as they were directed
against military facilities of Yugoslavia instead of the Yugoslav
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether NATO will send ground troops to Kosovo, the NATO
chief said that ground troops might be deployed to help ethnic
Albanian refugees return home if a ceasefire agreement could be
reached.
</P>
<P>
He, however, acknowledged that sending ground troops would be a
difficult decision.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes Y Juan
ruled out the possibility of sending ground troops to Kosovo,
saying that it was a risky action which would only lead to heavy
casualties. 
</P>
