<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees Lowest Inflation in 5 Years in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in March in Thailand
rose year-on-year by just 1.6 percent, the lowest rate in at least
five years, according to the Thai Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of this year, the rate was 2.6 percent,
well below the official forecast of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The stability of the baht was a major factor behind the low
rate, Vithoon Tulayanondha, deputy director of the ministry's
Department of Business Economics, was quoted Friday by the Bangkok
Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The baht has been trading between 27 and 38 to the U.S. dollar
for several months, compared with 49 baht in March last year and a
peak of 57 baht in January last year.
</P>
<P>
The monthly Consumer Price Index in March also fell by 0.2
percent from February, due largely to a 0.9-percent decline in
food prices.
</P>
<P>
Vithoon said the index in April was expected to decline from
March because of the reduction of the value-added tax (VAT) to 7
percent from 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The VAT cuts would reduce the prices of products by about 2.73
percent overall, the department has calculated.
</P>
<P>
The department also announced that the country's wholesale
price index in March fell by 0.5 percent from February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0254 </DOCNO>
