<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of the Macao SAR Basic Law (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- This is the fifth in a question
and answer series on the ABCs of the Basic Law of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
How does the Basic Law reflect the "one country, two systems"
policy?
</P>
<P>
The "one country, two systems" policy serves as both the policy
basis and essence of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law first and foremost gives expression to the "one
country" principle.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Basic Law stipulates that the MSAR is an
inalienable part of the People's Republic of China and is directly
under the Central People's Government.
</P>
<P>
The Central People's Government maintains sole responsibility
for the MSAR's foreign affairs and defense, and will appoint or
remove the Chief Executive, the principal government official and
Procurator-General for the MSAR in accordance with the relevant
provisions in the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
National laws listed in Annex III to the Basic Law will be
applied in the MSAR. The Chief Executive of the MSAR, as well as
the region's principal government officials, President and Vice
President of the Legislative Council, President of the Court of
Final Appeals, Procurator-General and members of the Executive
Council must be Chinese citizens with permanent residency in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law adheres to the "one country" principle and
contains explicit provisions to ensure fulfillment of the "two
systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Basic Law stipulates that MSAR will exercise a
high degree of autonomy and enjoy executive, legislative and
independent judicial power, including the power of final
adjudication in accordance with the Law.
</P>
<P>
The MSAR's executive branch and legislature will be composed of
permanent residents in Macao in accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The socialist system and related policies will not be practiced
in MSAR, and the existing capitalist system and way of life in the
region will remain unchanged for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Laws previously in force in Macao will be maintained, with the
exception of laws which contravene the Basic Law or which are
otherwise subject to amendments by the legislature or relevant
departments in the MSAR in accordance with legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
The government of the MSAR will be responsible for the
maintaining public order in the region. The Basic Law clearly
stipulated the basic rights and obligations of residents in the
MSAR.
</P>
<P>
The MSAR will maintain independent finances and will formulate
economic, social, scientific and technological, culture and
educational policies.
</P>
<P>
Courts in the MSAR shall interpret on their own, in
adjudicating cases and the provisions in the Basic Law which the
limits of the region's autonomy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
