<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of the Macao SAR Basic Law (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- This is the sixth in a question
and answer series on the ABCs of the Basic Law of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Is the Basic Law a local law?
</P>
<P>
Some people are under the misconception that the Basic Law is
simply a local law concerning various systems in the MSAR and has
no relationship with other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Determining whether a law is national or local is based on
content and the enacting legislative body. All laws enacted by the
national legislature National People's Congress are national laws.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law, adopted by the National People's Congress,
China's highest legislative body, is a national law. Therefore,
the Basic Law not only applies to the MSAR, but also to all
provinces, autonomous regions and cities with provincial status in
China.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Macao and other parts of China, as well as
national and local government agencies and people's organizations
should study and understand the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
A good understanding of the Basic Law will ensure a true
appreciation of the "one country, two systems" principle, as
provision for enforcing and upholding of the authority and
sanctity of the Law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
