<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asia to See More Bank Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A wave of bank mergers is sweeping
across Asia, where one-third to a half of banks will either
acquire, or be acquired over the next two years as a result of
industry restructuring and consolidation, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
During the past few months, a merger and acquisition (M&AMP;A)
storm has already hit Asia's banking system. Seventeen thrift
banks in the Philippines are planning to merge into "a super
thrift bank."
</P>
<P>
Also, the Philippine Commercial International Bank, the
country's third largest bank in terms of capital, is putting its
shares on the auction block. A number of local and foreign banks
have expressed their strong desire to acquire a majority stake in
the bank.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, five private banks have agreed to merge into "a
power bank."
</P>
<P>
Indonesian bankers expect the number of banks in their country
to shrink to 30 or fewer by 2002, from nearly 150 banks today.
</P>
<P>
What has produced the sweeping wave?
</P>
<P>
First, two years after the financial crisis broke out, Asian
banks remain in dire need of capital, but are shut out of the
capital market.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, commercial banks suffered a loss of 12.3
billion U.S. dollars in 1998 and have to seek outside investors
for recapitalization.
</P>
<P>
Second, Asian governments are encouraging bank restructuring
and are courting foreign investments in local banks to revive the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
Third, Asian banks' 1 trillion dollars of non-performing loans
are forcing some of them to be acquired by local or foreign
investors for survival.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, the banking sector needs 30 billion dollars to
resolve the issue of non-performing loans, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, necessary conditions in countries like South Korea,
Thailand and Indonesia are becoming ripe with the deepening of
banking reforms, as they are opening their financial markets and
allowing foreign investors to buy part or, a majority of bank
shares.
</P>
<P>
In the M&AMP;A process, foreigner players are more aggressive than
the local ones. DBS Bank of Singapore has snapped up banks in
Thailand, Hong Kong and the Philippines. Major global players
ABN-Amro and GE Capital have announced several deals in Asia and
are looking for more.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to be opportunistic in our acquisitions but
we will be careful about small- and medium-sized banks," said John
Olds, vice-president and chief executive officer of DBS Bank of
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Observers said foreign players are seeking to take advantage of
the current crisis to secure a growth platform in the region. In
1998, acquisitions by American and European players grew to 1.1
billion dollars from a mere 80 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The amount of M&AMP;A activities by foreign investors will
definitely increase in the next two years, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
So far the deals have been largely with strategic partners from
foreign countries, especially from the United States and Europe,
rather than so-called "venture" investors, who have no strategic
agenda but simply look for cheap assets and sell them for a
profit.
</P>
<P>
"We are investing in established businesses that are decent and
of good quality but which may be facing difficulties," said Tan
Beien Kiat, the Singapore-based regional managing director of
Newbridge Capital.
</P>
<P>
With a large-scale "foreign invasion" into the Asian banking
industry, many local businessmen do not welcome new partners as
they believe it would be hard for many of the new comers to break
the habit of running to the capital markets or banks for cheap
money to fund their needs.
</P>
<P>
But economists generally believe that the increased M&AMP;A
activities by foreigners are beneficial for the restructuring and
consolidation of the region's banking system.
</P>
<P>
Without M&AMP;A activities, either by local or foreign investors,
the banking sector in many Asian countries would take much longer
time to revive, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anhui Records Rising Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province recorded
a foreign trade volume of 305 million US dollars for the first two
months of the year, up 12.2 percent on the 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
The export volume for the period jumped 12.4 percent to 193
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The province has exerted extensive efforts to develop European
and American markets in a bid to minimize the impact of the
financial crisis engulfing Asia.
</P>
<P>
Exports to East Europe surged 244 percent on an annual basis
during the period, with the volume to North America rising 24.7
percent and exports to Asia climbing 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The province has restructured its exports mix and increased
exports of vessels, machine tools,castings, cotton and wool.
</P>
<P>
General trade accounted for 76 percent of total exports, with
related trade growing by 25.7 percent on the previous year's
period to 147 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
State enterprises accounted for 79.3 percent of the total
export volume. Exports for related enterprises jumped 8.8 percent
on the 1998 period to 153 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
