<HEADLINE> Czech Former Soccer Tycoon Charged with Tax Evasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Former Czech soccer tycoon Petr
Mach has been charged with tax evasion and insurance fraud, the
state prosecutor's office said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mach, former owner of Sparta Prague, could face up to 12 years
in jail if convicted of failing to pay customs duty when he bought
a luxury BMW in Germany seven years ago, said the prosecutor's
spokesman Martin Omelka.
</P>
<P>
Mach allegedly later sold the car in Ukraine and claimed it had
been stolen.
</P>
<P>
Mach also got a 4.3 million US dollars loan from a Czech bank
to buy buses for his company and later sold the buses to another
company, allegedly concealing they were being held as collateral
by the bank, the prosecutor's office said.
</P>
<P>
Mach bought Sparta in 1992 and sold it four years later to a
Slovak steel concern for a record 1 billion koruna (30 million US
dollars). He has retired from soccer and pursues horse racing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
