<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Chief Charged over Cycling Doping Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- French cycling federation (FFC)
chief Daniel Baal was charged in connection with the 1998 Tour de
France doping scandal in Lille, France, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Baal, the 13th person to be placed under investigation, was
charged with "complicity in helping others to obtain and use
illegal performance enhancing substances," judicial sources said.
</P>
<P>
FFC vice-president Roger Legeay and leading rider Richard
Virenque, formerly with Festina team and now with the Italian
Polti team, were charged earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Tour de France director Jean-Marie Leblanc, detained for
questioning earlier on Thursday, was not charged after being heard
by magistrate Patrick Keil later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Baal, saying he had done all he could against the practice of
doping in the sport, said: "This charge is unjust and absolutely
unfounded."
</P>
<P>
Baal said he had asked the French sports ministry for an
increase in anti-doping controls and thought some of those charged
were trying to implicate others to try to reduce their
responsibility in the affair.
</P>
<P>
Last year's Tour, won by Italian Marco Pantani, came close to
being abandoned halfway because of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Several teams were expelled or withdrew and only half the
riders who started the race reached the Champs Elysees finish in
Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
