<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgages Making Shanghai's Housing More Affordable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Out of 20 houses available for a
real estate sale, 18 were auctioned off on Tuesday in Shanghai in
China's first sale of houses that come with a bank mortgage.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 people were present and 254 bid against each
other for nearly an hour. The auction ended with 3.62 million yuan
worth of sales.
</P>
<P>
After a dozen bids and ever increasing prices, one 59-year-old
woman, Li Xiuzhen, finally won one deal. She got a 105-sq. m.
house on the outskirts of Shanghai. "Without the Construction Bank
of China mortgage," she explains while signing the contract, "I
can't imagine how I could afford the house."
</P>
<P>
She paid 1,950 yuan per square meter, nearly 700 yuan below the
market value. "The deal was attractive," she adds, "because the
amortization dramatically eases the debt pressure."
</P>
<P>
The 18 buyers are mostly ordinary citizens like Li. Their 10-
year loans come from the Huangpu branch of the Construction Bank
of China. Zhang Enzhao, the president of the Shanghai branch, says
that the bank has provided as much as 2 million yuan in loans for
the auction and will provide more for houses in future.
</P>
<P>
Fan Ganping, the vice-president of the Shanghai International
Commodity Auction Company, the auctioneer, says that the Shanghai
branches of other banks also have mortgage services available for
real estate auctions, as part of an effort to help more local
people realize their dream of having their own house.
</P>
<P>
Real estate auctions, which only began to appear in Shanghai in
the past 2 years, grew rapidly, partly thanks to the knock-down
auction prices that were in many cases 30 percent below the market
price.
</P>
<P>
Potential buyers always faced immense difficulties in the past
with a lump-sum payment and this in turn greatly inhibited the
growth of the local real estate business, including auctions. In
the past, there were often no more than 50 bidders at an auction.
</P>
<P>
Yao Guanghai, a State Administration of Internal Trade official,
says that providing mortgages for auctions benefits both
auctioneers and citizens and that it really deserves to be
promoted in the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Housing is one of the major problems for the people of Shanghai
and they have an increasing awareness of home ownership. Per-
capita residential space in Shanghai was 9 sq. m. at the end of
1997.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai had 16.2 billion yuan in outstanding housing loans by
the end of 1998, a jump of 117 percent from the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
