Staff of the Romanian Army, and Elena Zamfirescu, Romanian Foreign
Ministry state secretary. (Romania-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The European Troika Foreign Ministers with their
counterparts from eight Southeast European countries Thursday
after a meeting appealed closest cooperation between the states
and organizations involved to provide emergency aid for Kosovo
refugees.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, in German town of Petersberg, on humanitarian
issues and stability in Balkan region was held between European
Troika, which stands for Austria, Germany and Finland,
respectively the former, present and next rotating president of EU,
and Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia of Federal
Yugoslavia, Hungary, Romania, Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Top goal of the meeting was to coordinate measures to stabilize
the region and improve the situation of Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) commissar for humanitarian issues Emma
Bonino, the United Nations (UN) refugee commissar Sadako Ogata,
and officials of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE) attended the meeting. (Germany-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Office of the U.S. Trade Representative (
USTR) released on Thursday its annual report on foreign trade
barriers, saying the country's major trading partners continue to
have unfair practices that hurt U.S. exports of goods, services
and farm products.
</P>
<P>
The report lists the so-called unfair trade practices which the
USTR said are harmful to American exports by 54 trading partners,
including its six largest: Canada, China, the European Union (EU),
Japan, South Korea and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The report called South Korea "one of the toughest markets in
the world for doing business." It commended the current Korean
administration for implementing efforts to put its economy on a
more open, market-oriented basis, in response to the Asian
financial crisis. (US-Foreign Trade)
</P>
<P>
