<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Bronson Fails Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- American Bryan Bronson has been
suspended after a positive doping test in Rome on July 14, the
International Amateur Athletic Federation said in Monaco on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bronson, the world's leading 400 meters hurdler, finished third
at the 1997 world championships in Athens, and clocked the third
fastest time ever of 47.03 seconds in winning the U.S. title in
New Orleans last June.
</P>
<P>
But after winning in Rome in the following month, Bronson's
urine sample was found to have "abnormal steroid concentrations",
and has been suspended on March 19 this year, said IAAF spokesman
Giorgio Reineri.
</P>
<P>
To explaine the eight-month delay between the positive test
finding and the decision of suspension, Reineri said: "This is a
very delicate case.
</P>
<P>
"After he tested positive, Bronson was asked to explain himself.
He sent to us an explanation from his lawyer and a doctor, saying
that he had some medical problem. We took the decision not to
suspend him immediately, but to await a full medical report.
</P>
<P>
Bronson, 26, was allowed to race all last season, despite the
positive test findings.
</P>
<P>
"We waited for nearly six months to receive his medical report,
" Reinari said. "The medical report was never sent, and it was
impossible for us to reach Bronson, and so we have suspended him."
</P>
<P>
Bronson is the third top athlete to be suspended for drug use
in the past month.
</P>
<P>
Vita Pavlysh, the Ukrainian who won the women's shot put at
last month's world indoor championships in Japan, was stripped of
her title following a positive test.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the British governing body UK Athletics announced
that European 200 metres champion Doug Walker had been suspended
pending a hearing following a positive test for the anabolic
steroid nandrolone after an out-of-competition test last December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
