<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Sentences Salvadoran Terrorist to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Salvadoran Otto Rene Rodriguez
Llerena, who confessed to two acts of terrorism in the Cuban
capital, Havana, was condemned to death Thursday in a Havana court.
</P>
<P>
Under Cuban law, the death sentence will be appealed routinely
before the Supreme Court, and then before the State Council, the
highest judicial entity in the island.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez confessed to placing a bomb in a central Havana hotel
in 1997 and trying to introduce explosives to Cuba in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The trial had heard evidence not only of the Salvadoran ex-
soldier's crime, but also of his ties with the anti-Castro
American Cuban Foundation (FNCA) based in Miami.
</P>
<P>
During the trial process it was determined that Rodriguez
intended, in his second journey to the island, to place devices at
the memorial to the Argentine-Cuban guerrilla, Ernesto "Che"
Guevara, in Santa Clara city, some 270 kilometers east of Havana.
</P>
<P>
The seriousness of the events had the district attorney change
at request for a 30-year jail sentence to the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
Another Salvadoran man, Raul Ernesto Cruz Leon, also paid by
the FNCA, was condemned to death last week for carrying out
dynamite bombings in five hotels and a restaurant in Havana.
</P>
<P>
Cruz Leon, whose actions caused the death of an Italian tourist
and injuries to 11 others, is now awaiting the Supreme Court's
decision after the routine appeal under Cuban law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
