<HEADLINE> Myanmar Imports Large Amount of Edible Oil in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar imported a large amount of
edible oil in 1998, valued at 121.7 million U.S. dollars,
according to the latest official figures published by the
country's Central Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar cultivates more than 650,000 hectares of edible oil
crops annually, of which 450,000 hectares are peanuts and 200,000
hectares sunflowers.
</P>
<P>
While Myanmar's population increased by 1.84 percent annually,
the cultivated areas of edible oil crops did not expand
correspondingly and per-hectare output was lower, thus unable to
meet demand.
</P>
<P>
In order to promote the development of agriculture and enable
self-sufficiency in food and edible oil, Myanmar has leased out
free of charge to private entrepreneurs large plots of vacant,
virgin and fallow lands as well as wetlands for reclamation and
cultivation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
