<HEADLINE> U.S. Religious Leaders Seek Halt to Bombing for Easter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Roman Catholic and Serbian
Orthodox religious leaders urged Yugoslavia and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) to resume peace talks as their
congregations began Easter observances Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In joint letters to U.S. President Bill Clinton and Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, Eight Catholic cardinals called for
a cessation of hostilities between Yugoslavia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, five Serbian Orthodox bishops who preside over the
North American branch of the Serbian Orthodox Church urged Clinton
and other NATO leaders to stop aerial bombing in Yugoslavia during
the Easter season.
</P>
<P>
"We implore you to suspend the bombing campaign beginning today
and at least through April 12," the Orthodox bishops said in a
statement. "This will provide for an opportunity to restart
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Serbian Orthodox Church asked a federal court in
Chicago to halt the air attacks, saying that bombs are falling on
sacred relics and icons. But a judge refused to hold an emergency
hearing, ruling the court had no jurisdiction over political and
military operations.
</P>
<P>
In their letter to Milosevic, the Catholic cardinals said
Serbian "military and police operations against the population of
Kosovo should cease immediately." They also asked Clinton for a
NATO cease-fire and said "no time must be lost in an effort to
return to the negotiating table."
</P>
<P>
Both letters urged the convening of a peace conference
involving other states in the region and the United Nations
because any settlement would require the creation of an
international peacekeeping force. 
</P>
