<HEADLINE> Jordan Cannot be a Hornet Player-Owner at Same Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan cannot play for
the Charlotte Hornets if he buys a 50 percent share of the team,
the retired superstar's agent said today.
</P>
<P>
"There's absolutely no truth to it," David Falk said of a
report that Jordan was considering coming out of retirement and
becoming a player-owner for the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
According to a local report, NBA league's rules forbid players
from owning teams, as Magic Johnson learned three years ago. This
would prevent any possibilities for Jordan from being a player-
owner even if he desire to do so.
</P>
<P>
Charles Barkley, Jordan's close friend, said: "First of all,
Jordan is not good enough to make that team win anyway. They need
the old Michael Jordan, the guy from five or six years ago, to
make that team a contender.
</P>
<P>
"He's the greatest player to ever play the game, and he would
only do himself a disservice. I just hope he doesn't play because
he'd damage his legendary status."
</P>
<P>
Hornets spokesman Harold Kaufman said: "The Michael Jordan and
George Shinn negotiations have never involved a playing role for
Jordan."
</P>
<P>
People who have seen Jordan recently estimate he is about 20
pounds heavier than his playing weight, and he recently said he
hasn't picked up a basketball since hitting the final shot of the
game winner at the NBA Finals last year.
</P>
<P>
Jordan also recently underwent surgery on his right finger.
</P>
<P>
The Hornets have collapsed this season. Its boss Shinn has been
going through a divorce and battling numerous sexual harassment
allegations, coach Dave Cowens resigned, Anthony Mason has missed
the entire season, and the team's best player Glen Rice was traded
to the Lakers for Elden Campbell and Eddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
The team seems certain to miss the postseason for the first
time since 1995-96. 
</P>
</TEXT>
