<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Higher On Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved higher
Thursday as investors were encouraged by corporate merger
announcements and economic reports.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 46.35 to 9,832.51
after moving into positive and negative territory several times
during the trading. The index rose nearly 54 points in early
trading and fell more than 10 points then.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 7.35 at 1,293.72 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index was up 31.97 at 2,493.37.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 1.40 at 604.99 and the American
Stock Exchange index rose 1.00 at 711.30. The Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies rose 1.11 at 398.74.
</P>
<P>
During the most day of trading, investors were worried about
NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia and the scheduled release of
March employment data on Friday. But merger announcements and
economic reports overcome the worries among investors before the
end of trading, lifting the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Among the merger announcements were BP Amoco's plan to buy
Atlantic Richfield for 26.6 billion U.S. dollars to create the
world's second-largest oil company and Yahoo's planned purchase of
Broadcast.com for 5.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Commerce Department reported that U.S.
personal income increased a seasonally adjusted 0.5 percent in
February after a 0.6 percent rise in January. Meanwhile, consumer
spending jumped 0.7 percent after a 0.4 percent rise in the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by 1,537 to 1,467 with
557 unchanged on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 701.10 million shares from 922.1
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The New York Stock Exchange is closed Friday in observance of
Good Friday. 
</P>
