<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USTR Report Lists Unfair Trade Practices by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Office of the U.S. Trade
Representative (USTR) released on Thursday its annual report on
foreign trade barriers, saying the country's major trading
partners continue to have unfair practices that hurt U.S. exports
of goods, services and farm products.
</P>
<P>
The report lists the so-called unfair trade practices which the
USTR said are harmful to American exports by 54 trading partners,
including its six largest: Canada, China, the European Union (EU),
Japan, South Korea and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
On Canada, the United States' single largest trading partner,
the report said that Canadian market has been opened to a
significant degree by the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement and the
North America Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, impediments to U.S. goods and services
remain, including certain aspects of the Canadian agriculture
regime such as the Canadian Wheat Board, and Canada's failure to
provide adequate copyright and patent protection.
</P>
<P>
As for its economic relationship with Europe, "the largest and
most complex in the world," the administration said that battles
with the European Union over bananas and beef have "not only hurt
U.S. exports but have undermined the credibility of the WTO
dispute settlement system."
</P>
<P>
Despite hundreds of billions of dollars that are exchanged
unhindered in annual two-way trade and investments, the report
found that "the EU's protectionist agriculture policies are likely
to continue to cause disputes, unless addressed in upcoming
multilateral trade negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The report, in its segment on Japan, said the country continues
to make opening its markets to U.S. exports a top priority,
"emphasizing the need for implementation of fiscal stimulus and
reform of Japan's financial sector." It said the administration
would press Japan to implement further deregulation measures in
telecommunications, medical devices, housing and pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
The report called South Korea "one of the toughest markets in
the world for doing business." It commended the current Korean
administration for implementing efforts to put its economy on a
more open, market-oriented basis, in response to the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Resistance to key trade reforms remains, however, and many
issues have arisen on Korea's compliance with its international
obligations," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The USTR said the report will serve as a foundation for its
efforts to reduce and eliminate unfair trade practices worldwide
through negotiation of agreements and action to enforce
agreements.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said she hoped
the report "will help all Americans interested in trade to work
together to develop a strategy that meets our country's needs in a
new century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990402.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
