<HEADLINE> Canada Wants to See How U.N. Might Be Involved in  Addressing Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Minister
Lloyd Axworthy Thursday said that his visit to the United Nations
is to "see how the United Nations and the Security Council might
be involved in addressing the Kosovo crisis."
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his talks with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
the Canadian foreign minister told reporters that Annan is
expected to produce a report of assessment of the humanitarian
situation surrounding the Kosovo crisis next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian minister said he also discussed with Annan on the
refugees who crossed the border into Albania and Macedonia. "We
discussed how the situation degenerates in Montenegro (a Yugoslav
republic), Albania and Macedonia" because of the refugee exodus
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Apart from his discussion with the U.N. chief on the latest
situation in Kosovo, a Serbian province, the Canadian foreign
minister also met with the president of the Security Council for
the month of April, Alain Dejammet of France, as well as
ambassadors from several other countries.
</P>
<P>
Canada is a member of NATO, which is waging air strikes on
Yugoslavia, a sovereign and independent member of the U.N. family.
</P>
<P>
The NATO military attacks are followed by an exodus of refugees
from Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians, who make up some 90 percent
of the province's population of 2 million, have been fighting with
Serbs for independence.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the foreign minister said, "Canada has pushed for
active Security Council engagement in the Kosovo crisis... We will
continue to counsult with the U.N. on ways in which the Council
might take action on the dire humanitarian situation in the
region."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that he also met with the Brazilian
permanent representative to the United Nations, Celso Amorim, to
discuss the work of the two panels he chairs on weapons
inspections and humanitarian conditions in Iraq, as well as the
third panel dealing with Kuwaiti missing persons and property
resulting from the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
It was at Canada's suggestion that these panels were
established in late January in a bid to break a deadlock in the
Council over how to proceed on the Iraq issue.  
</P>
