<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Murder Gets Life Sentence by British Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A 78-year-old man was sentenced to
life imprisonment on Thursday after Britain's first full war
crimes trial convicted him of killing Jews during World War Two.
</P>
<P>
The Old Bailey jury in London found former railway employee
Anthony Sawoniuk guilty on two charges of murder. Sawoniuk came to
Britain in 1946 and lived in south London.
</P>
<P>
During the course of a one-year trial, the prosecution said
Sawoniuk, at the time a policeman, enthusiastically carried out
Nazi policies of genocide against Jews in his home town of
Domachevo in Nazi-occupied Belarus in 1942.
</P>
<P>
"Though you held a lowly rank in the hierarchy of those
involved in the liquidation of Jews in eastern Europe, to the Jews
of Domachevo it must have seemed otherwise," Judge Francis Potts
said in passing two life sentences.
</P>
<P>
The defence contended that Sawoniuk was forced to volunteer for
the Domachevo police force, organised by Nazi Germany, in order to
avoid deportation and forced labor.
</P>
<P>
Sawoniuk is half-blind and deaf and may serve his sentence in a
prison hospital.
</P>
<P>
Detective Superintendent Michael Griffiths, who headed the
investigation which involved a visit to Belarus by the jury and
witnesses travelling to London from Israel and Belarus, said the
conviction was a victory for past injustices.
</P>
<P>
"Today's verdict has shown all those involved in murder that
irrespective of the passage of time, justice will be done,"
Griffiths said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
