<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Fears Funding Cut in Pakistan's Social Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. resident coordinator Robert
England Friday expressed fears for drastic cuts in Pakistan's
Social Action Plan (SAP) due to its economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference here, England asked Pakistan not
sit back with relief over the loan rescheduling by the Paris and
London Club.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is seriously concerned that the SAP may be
shortened under the present policy environment, which is already
only less than 2 percent of the Gross Domestic Product.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. coordinator feared that SAP would be the victim of
reform program undermining long-term human development in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government should not slash its SAP's funds, he
said.
</P>
<P>
England expressed the apprehension that Pakistan's short-term
stabilization of the economy will squeeze long-term development
priorities, human development will be jeopardized, poverty will
increase and long-term development prospects will be seriously
undermined.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, needs to work on economic reforms but at the
same time it must address issues of poverty and human development.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan must come out of the debt trap, generate economic
growth and create investment and employment opportunities," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United Nations believes that to address the
issues of poverty, the government must ensure people's access to
opportunities in all sectors.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. coordinator called for a national poverty reduction
program in order to balance the reform program.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the Pakistani government will put forward a
national strategy to address poverty.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the recent census showed that Pakistan is
entering demographic transition and population growth rate is now
2.6 percent coming down from 3 percent in the early 90s.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, that Pakistan's population is expected to
reach 250 to 300 million by the year 2025, putting pressure on
resources.
</P>
<P>
He described primary education as the best way to invest in
human development.
</P>
<P>
England believed that Pakistan economic reform plans under a
rescue package negotiated with the International Monetary Fund is
likely to raise the poverty levels and hinder social and human
development.
</P>
<P>
SAP seeks to provide basic education and health to the poor and
represents about 80 percent of all social development spending in
Pakistan's public sector.
</P>
<P>
England said he would urge Pakistan not to allow the spending
to slip, and hoped the Pakistani government would come out with a
national strategy to address poverty, because more than 30 percent
of Pakistan's 130 million people still live below the poverty
line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
