<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poppy Production in Pakistan Down Dramatically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Poppy production in Pakistan has
been brought down from 80,000 tons to 500 tons and will be
completely eliminated by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has taken effective and pragmatic steps to achieve the
goal of eliminating poppy cultivation and destruction of heroin
laboratories, said Tariq Aziz, secretary of the Interior Ministry
responsible for narcotics control.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the media here on Friday, Aziz said reducing the
demand of illicit drugs through preventive education campaign to
save about 4.3 million drug addicts is the government's high
priority.
</P>
<P>
"We have almost eliminated poppy cultivation in Pakistan mainly
because of substantial assistance extended by the United Nations
Drug Control Program, the U.S. and Britain," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said it is now a big headache to control drug
smuggling from Afghanistan although international agencies were
considering various proposals to eliminate poppy cultivation in
Afghanistan and its smuggling to other countries.
</P>
<P>
He said elimination of illicit crop involves alternative
development programs in order to direct the channel of cultivation
from illicit to licit crops.
</P>
<P>
The main emphasis should be on agro-based industries, food
crops and livestock accompanied by necessary infrastructure, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The government recently approved the Drug Abuse Control Master
Plan which is a strategy for control of narcotics over a period of
five years upto the year of 2003, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives of the plan include reducing the demand for
illicit drugs through a campaign by creating general awareness,
undertaking harm reduction treatment and rehabilitation programs
for addicts, and controlling the supply and production of
narcotics through total eradication of opium poppy crops by the
year of 2000. 
</P>
